Registration
************

Registering AmIRC
=================

You may use AmIRC freely for a period of up to 30 days to evaluate the
package. After those 30 days, you must either register AmIRC or stop
using it completely. During the trial period, AmIRC is limited to an
on-line time of 30 minutes, besides that, no functions are disabled.

To register AmIRC, see the included registration utility and assorted
documentation. It has all the necessary info and prices.  You can also
register on-line at @{b}http://www.vapor.com/@{ub}.

Use a credit card and have your keyfile in minutes!


@EndNode

@Node "Installation" "AmIRC.guide/Installation"
@Next "Connecting"
@Prev "Registration"
@Toc "Main"

Installation
************

How to install AmIRC
====================

It is strongly suggested that you use AmIRC's installer script. This
will make sure all necessary files are in the correct place and will
make sure you will have AmIRC up and running in no time.  The installer
script requires that you have the Amiga installer utility (version 43.3
or later).  Once you've unpacked the AmIRC archive you can start the
installation by simply clicking on the install icon in the AmIRC
drawer. The installation script will ask you some questions, depending
on the experience level you've selected at the start, simply answer
them and the installer will do the rest.

If you cannot or prefer not to use the installer utility, a manual
install is relatively simple, just move the contents of the archive to a
directory of your choice and it's ready to use. If you have met the
@{"requirements" Link "Requirements"} for the optimized version of AmIRC, delete the AmIRC file
and rename "AmIRC020" as "AmIRC".  You might want to copy the "MUI"
directory of the AmIRC distribution to MUI:Libs/MUI/ to avoid version
confusion.


@EndNode

@Node "Connecting" "AmIRC.guide/Connecting"
@Next "Operation"
@Prev "Installation"
@Toc "Main"

Connecting
**********

Let's have a (first) go
=======================

Once you have @{"installed" Link "Installation"} AmIRC, you can start the program from WB by
clicking on its icon. After a few moments you will be presented with the
Server Selection Window. You will need to enter some data into the
gadgets of this window in order for AmIRC to be able to log you onto an
IRC network. First and foremost you will need to think up some witty
and original nickname or handle by which you will be known during your
IRC session(s). Make sure you pick an original one as some networks
don't allow different users sharing the same name and won't allow you
to connect until you try with a name that is not being used. You can
supply AmIRC with 4 nicknames which it will subsequently use to try and
connect to the network. You also need to provide AmIRC some additional
information like your real name (be honest here!). If your TCP/IP stack
is already running an @{i}IdentD@{ui} service then you won't need to provide
your user name as AmIRC will get it from the stack and the @{i}IdentD@{ui}
gadget will be ghosted.  Now you are ready to connect AmIRC to an IRC
network. Either select a network and server from the list provided or
enter the details of your own favourite server.


@EndNode

@Node "Operation" "AmIRC.guide/Operation"
@Next "IRC Terms"
@Prev "Connecting"
@Toc "Main"

Operation
*********

Operation at a glance
=====================

The main AmIRC user interface is laid out in a logical, intuitive
manner, making it easy to use. Here's an overview of the main interface:

   @{b}*@{ub} The main feature of the interface is the @{b}Text Listview@{ub}, where all
     incoming text is displayed.

   @{b}*@{ub} Directly below this is the @{b}Textinput Gadget@{ub}, labelled with the
     nickname that you have chosen. Any text entered here will be sent
     out to the IRC server.

   @{b}*@{ub} Directly next to the textinput gadget is the @{b}Logging Button@{ub} marked
     'L'.  Clicking on it activates the logging of that window to a
     file.

   @{b}*@{ub} To the right of the listview is a @{b}Scroll Gadget@{ub}, which enables you
     to scroll backward through the text in the listview.

   @{b}*@{ub} At the top left of the listview is a the @{b}Channelname Gadget@{ub} that
     shows the name of the channel that you have joined.

   @{b}*@{ub} To the right of the channel name, is the @{b}Topic Input/Display
     Gadget@{ub}, where the topic of a joined channel is displayed.
     Many channels have topic protection, which means only channel
     operators can change the topic. If you can enter text in the topic
     bar (either because the topic isn't protected or you are a channel
     operator) you may change the topic of the channel by entering the
     topic in this gadget, and hitting the 'Enter' key.

   @{b}*@{ub} To the right of the topic input gadget are the@{b}Channel Mode
     Buttons@{ub}, which display the current modes for the joined
     channel.  Users with Channel Operator (Ops) status may also use
     these buttons to change the current channel modes.

        -     @{b}T - Topic Protection@{ub}: Toggles Topic Protection on/off. If
          on, the topic can be changed by Channel Operators (Ops) only.

        -     @{b}N - No Messaging@{ub}: Toggles Messaging on/off. If active, a
          user can only write to the channel if they have joined it.

        -     @{b}S - Secret@{ub}: Toggles Secret mode on/off. If active, the
          channel is invisible until it is joined.

        -     @{b}I - Invite Only@{ub}: Toggles Invite Only mode on/off. If
          active, users can only join after they have been invited.

        -     @{b}P - Private@{ub}: Toggles Private mode on/off. If active, the
          channel will be invisible in the global channel list.

        -     @{b}M - Moderated@{ub}: Toggles Moderated mode on/off. If active,
          only channel operators (Ops) and users with 'voice' can type
          to the channel.

        -     @{b}L - Limit@{ub}: Sets a limited number of users allowed on the
          channel

        -     @{b}K - Keyword@{ub}: Toggles Keyword mode on/off. If active,
          Users can only join the channel if they give the correct
          keyword.

        -     @{b}B - Ban@{ub}: Sets/Displays the current Bans active on the
          channel

   @{b}*@{ub} Below the channel mode buttons is the @{b}User Listview@{ub}, which shows a
     current list of users on the joined channel. Double clicking on a
     users name will perform a @{"/WHOIS" Link "WHOIS"} on that user. Clicking once on a
     users name will set that user as the default to perform other
     operations on, such as an operation from the configurable user
     buttons. Pressing the right mouse button when on a name shows a
     menu where you can select the same functions as the User Buttons
     below.

   @{b}*@{ub} Directly below the User Listview is the @{b}Lag-O-Meter@{ub}. This meter
     indicates how much lag there is on your connection. Double
     clicking on it will bring up the INFO window.

   @{b}*@{ub} Below the Lag-O-Meter are the @{b}User Buttons@{ub}. These buttons are
     configurable from the @{"configuration" Link "Actions"} window, accessible by
     selecting 'Setup...' from the AmIRC @{"Settings" Link "Settings"} menu.

   @{b}*@{ub} You can Drag-Highlight text in the listview in order to paste it
     elsewhere.  you will need some type of snap utility such as
     Newedit or Powersnap in order to past the text into another
     application. The text is stored in the clipboard. To paste the
     text inside AmIRC you can use <right-amiga> V.

     The @{b}TAB@{ub} key will cycle through the names of people that have
     previously /MSG'ed you, and insert it into the textinput gadget.
     Simply enter your message after the "/MSG <user> " in order to
     @{"/MSG" Link "MSG"} them back.

     Entering ':' first in the textinput gadget will automatically
     publicly address the last person you typed to using the ':' after
     their nick.

For a full explanation of all AmIRC functions and windows please check
out the Reference section.


@EndNode

@Node "IRC Terms" "AmIRC.guide/IRC Terms"
@Next "Menus"
@Prev "Operation"
@Toc "Main"

IRC Terms
*********

Specific IRC vocabulary
=======================

Here's a list of some commonly used terms and expressions with their
respective explanation:

   @{b}*@{ub}     @{b}Action@{ub}: @{i}CTCP Action@{ui} command, executed by a @{"/ME" Link "ME"} at the
     beginning of a message.

   @{b}*@{ub}     @{b}Ban@{ub}: A @{i}channel mode@{ui} set in order to prevent a @{i}user@{ui} or group of
     users from joining a @{i}channel@{ui}.

   @{b}*@{ub}     @{b}Bot@{ub}: Short for Robot, a Bot is a @{i}script@{ui} that acts like a user,
     and can execute a command upon a certain occurrence.

   @{b}*@{ub}     @{b}Client@{ub}: Software that is written for the purpose of connecting
     to a @{i}server@{ui}, in this case, an @{i}IRC server@{ui}.

   @{b}*@{ub}     @{b}Channel@{ub}: A group of users on @{i}IRC@{ui}. A channel will have a name
     (i/e, #AmIRC), and may or may not have a @{i}topic@{ui} of conversation.

   @{b}*@{ub}     @{b}Channel Mode@{ub}: The properties of a @{i}channel@{ui} that allow or
     disallow certain activities. Channel Modes can only be changed or
     set by @{i}Channel@{ui} Operators. The available channel modes are:

        -     @{b}Invite Only@{ub}: If active, This mode allows users to join if
          they have been invited by someone in the channel.

        -     @{b}Private@{ub}: If active, the @{i}channel@{ui} is invisible in the
          global channel list.

        -     @{b}Lag@{ub}: The term which is used when the connection to a
          server or client is delayed.

        -     @{b}Limit@{ub}: If active, sets a limit on the number of @{i}users@{ui}
          allowed to join a @{i}channel@{ui}.

        -     @{b}Moderated@{ub}: If active, only @{i}Channel Operators@{ui} and @{i}users@{ui}
          with @{i}voice@{ui} may type input to the @{i}channel@{ui}.

        -     @{b}No Messaging@{ub}: If active, prevents @{i}users@{ui} from sending a
          message to the @{i}channel@{ui} until they have joined it.

        -     @{b}Secret@{ub}: If active, the @{i}channel@{ui} is invisible until it is
          joined.

        -     @{b}Topic Protection@{ub}: If active, only @{i}Channel Operators@{ui} may
          set or change the @{i}topic@{ui} of a @{i}channel@{ui}.

   @{b}*@{ub}     @{b}Channel Operator (or OP)@{ub}: A @{i}user@{ui} who has control over a
     @{i}channel@{ui}.  A user who creates a channel is given Op status, and
     in turn can give it to anyone else in the channel.

   @{b}*@{ub}     @{b}Chat Network@{ub}: A network of computers that are interconnected
     so that anyone on any server in the network may chat with anyone
     else on any computer in that same network.  Here's some major chat
     networks:

        -     @{b}ARCnet@{ub}: Amiga Relay Chat Network, partially running on
          Amiga servers.

        -     @{b}IRCnet@{ub}: Formerly part of EFnet, now split.

        -     @{b}EFnet@{ub}: Eris Free Network. The largest IRC network

        -     @{b}DAL-Net@{ub}: A different IRC network with some specialized
          functions that do not appear in typical IRC networks.

        -     @{b}Undernet@{ub}: An alternative IRC network

   @{b}*@{ub}     @{b}Command@{ub}: A message to an IRC server or to a local or remote
     client.  Commands generally begin with a /.  See @{"Commands" Link "Commands"}.

   @{b}*@{ub}     @{b}CTCP@{ub}: Client To Client Protocol, A standard for sending
     commands from one @{i}client@{ui} to another, usually for the purpose of
     getting information from the remote client. See @{"CTCP" Link "CTCP"}.

   @{b}*@{ub}     @{b}DCC@{ub}: Direct Client Connection - a standard for creating a
     direct link between two clients, for the purpose of sending or
     receiving files, or to carry a more secure conversation. See @{"DCC" Link "DCC"}.

   @{b}*@{ub}     @{b}IdentD@{ub}: IdentD is software that can be run on the client,
     allowing an IRC server to corroborate the identity of a client.
     AmIRC has an IdentD built in, and will automatically disable it if
     an external IdentD is running.

   @{b}*@{ub}     @{b}IRC@{ub}: Internet Relay Chat - Any @{i}Network@{ui} of Computers that run
     IRC @{i}servers@{ui} for the purpose of allowing @{i}users@{ui} to connect to it
     using @{i}client@{ui} software made for IRC.

   @{b}*@{ub}     @{b}Kick@{ub}: The occurrence of a @{i}user@{ui} being removed from a joined
     @{i}channel@{ui} by a @{i}channel operator@{ui}.

   @{b}*@{ub}     @{b}Lag@{ub}: Term to specify that the connection is delayed to some
     extend.

   @{b}*@{ub}     @{b}MOTD@{ub}: Message Of The Day, A message that may or may not be
     updated daily, that is meant to be read when connecting to an @{i}IRC
     server@{ui}.

   @{b}*@{ub}     @{b}Netsplit@{ub}: An event that occurs when a @{i}server@{ui} goes down that
     other servers depend on for network packets. Any servers that are
     dependant on the crashed server will split from the net, that is,
     they will still be up and running, with active @{i}clients@{ui}, but any
     clients on the other side of the crashed unit will appear to have
     all logged off at once.

   @{b}*@{ub}     @{b}Nick@{ub}: Short for Nickname, this is an alias that you may pick
     for yourself.

   @{b}*@{ub}     @{b}Op@{ub}: See @{i}Channel Operator@{ui}.

   @{b}*@{ub}     @{b}Server@{ub}: A computer that is Running IRC server software,
     allowing it to be connected to by @{i}IRC clients@{ui} or other servers.

   @{b}*@{ub}     @{b}Server Operator@{ub}: A person in control of an @{i}IRC server@{ui}.

   @{b}*@{ub}     @{b}TLA (Three Letter Abbreviations)@{ub}: Commonly used acronyms, not
     entirely restricted to 3 letters:

        -     @{b}AFAIK@{ub}: As Far As I Know

        -     @{b}AFK@{ub}: Away From Keyboard

        -     @{b}ASAP@{ub}: As Soon As Possible

        -     @{b}ATM@{ub}: At The Moment

        -     @{b}BRB@{ub}: (I'll) Be Right Back

        -     @{b}BBL@{ub}: (I'll) Be Back Later

        -     @{b}BBIAB@{ub}: (I'll) Be Back In A Bit

        -     @{b}BTW@{ub}: By The Way

        -     @{b}CU@{ub}: Or Cya, See You

        -     @{b}CUL@{ub}: Or CUL8R, See You Later, Catch You Later

        -     @{b}DL@{ub}: Or D/L, Download

        -     @{b}FAQ@{ub}: Frequently Asked Questions

        -     @{b}FWIW@{ub}: For What It's Worth

        -     @{b}FYI@{ub}: For Your Information

        -     @{b}IC@{ub}: I See

        -     @{b}IIRC@{ub}: If I Remember Correctly

        -     @{b}IMHO@{ub}: In My Humble|Honest Opinion

        -     @{b}L8R@{ub}: Later

        -     @{b}LOL@{ub}: Laughs Out Loud

        -     @{b}LTNS@{ub}: Long Time No See

        -     @{b}MOTD@{ub}: Message Of The Day

        -     @{b}NE1@{ub}: Anyone

        -     @{b}NP@{ub}: No Problem

        -     @{b}OTL@{ub}: Out To Lunch

        -     @{b}PLS@{ub}: Or PLZ, Please

        -     @{b}PPL@{ub}: People

        -     @{b}POV@{ub}: Point Of View

        -     @{b}RE@{ub}: Welcome back, short for @{i}Regards@{ui}

        -     @{b}ROTFL@{ub}: Rolls On The Floor Laughing

        -     @{b}RSN@{ub}: Real Soon Now

        -     @{b}RTFM@{ub}: Read The F***ing Manual

        -     @{b}TIA@{ub}: Thanks In Advance

        -     @{b}TNX@{ub}: Or Thnx, Thanks

        -     @{b}TTYL@{ub}: Talk To You Later

        -     @{b}TTFN@{ub}: Ta Ta For Now

        -     @{b}UL@{ub}: Or U/L, Upload

        -     @{b}WB@{ub}: Welcome Back

        -     @{b}WTF@{ub}: What(Why) The F***

   @{b}*@{ub}     @{b}Topic@{ub}: A heading for a @{i}channel@{ui} that may or may not have
     anything to do with the conversation at hand.

   @{b}*@{ub}     @{b}User@{ub}: A person using an @{i}IRC Client@{ui} to connect to a @{i}server@{ui} to
     chat.

   @{b}*@{ub}     @{b}User Mode@{ub}: Settings that affect a users properties.

        -     @{b}Invisible@{ub}: If this mode is set, a @{i}user@{ui} will be invisible
          in the global user list. The user will still be visible in
          the user list of any joined channel, however.

        -     @{b}Wallops@{ub}: When set, this mode will allow receiving of
          messages from the @{i}server operator@{ui} to all operators.

   @{b}*@{ub}     @{b}Userhost@{ub}: This is the string that defines a @{i}user@{ui}.  It consists
     of the user's chosen @{i}nick@{ui}, login name and domain name.  For example:
     Wupper!jwupper@monorail.denet234.de
     |      |       |        |      |_ Domain
     |      |       |        |________ Network
     |      |       |_________________ Machine
     |      |_________________________ Login
     |________________________________ Nick
   @{b}*@{ub}     @{b}Voice@{ub}: Status a normal (not an operator) user must have to
     type into a @{i}moderated@{ui} channel.


@EndNode

@Node "Menus" "AmIRC.guide/Menus"
@Next "Commands"
@Prev "IRC Terms"
@Toc "Main"

Menus
*****

What's on the menu?
===================


 @{" AmIRC " Link "AmIRC"}        AmIRC menu
 @{" Windows " Link "Windows"}      Windows menu
 @{" User Modes " Link "User Modes"}   User modes menu
 @{" Settings " Link "Settings"}     Settings menu
 @{" Plugins " Link "Plugins"}      Plugins menu
 @{" Rexx " Link "Rexx"}         Rexx menu


@EndNode

@Node "AmIRC" "AmIRC.guide/AmIRC"
@Toc "Menus"

Menus
=====

AmIRC Menu
----------

@{b}Select Server...@{ub}
     Opens the server window from which you can select various options
     for connecting to an IRC server. See @{"Connecting" Link "Connecting"}.

@{b}Reconnect@{ub}
     Reconnects to the previously selected server, without having to
     open de server window.

@{b}Disconnect@{ub}
     Disconnects you from the current server without having to quit
     AmIRC.

@{b}Logging Enabled?@{ub}
     Toggles logging on/off.

@{b}Iconify@{ub}
     Hides the AmIRC window either in an icon on the Workbench screen
     or in the WB Tools menu (selectable in MUI Prefs).

@{b}Help...@{ub}
     Opens Amirc.guide for reference while using AmIRC.

@{b}About AmIRC...@{ub}
     Opens a window with information about AmIRC and its Developer.
     Here you may connect to the AmIRC home page if your browser is
     running.

@{b}About MUI...@{ub}
     This will open a small window that displays information about the
     current version of MUI that is installed on your system, also,
     this window provides the option to register or update your MUI
     software.

@{b}Quit@{ub}
     Will close the current instance of AmIRC, leaving other instances
     open.


@EndNode

@Node "Windows" "AmIRC.guide/Windows"
@Toc "Menus"

Menus
=====

Windows Menu
------------

@{b}Channel Windows@{ub}
     If more than one AmIRC window is opened, you may select one here
     to pop it to front.

@{b}Dialog Windows@{ub}
     If any dialogue windows are open, you may select one here and
     bring it to front.

@{b}Windows List...@{ub}
     Shows the tray window where all windows are represented by a
     button. Hidden windows can be opened by double-clicking that
     window's button.

@{b}Channel List Window...@{ub}
     This will produce a window where you may list channels by min.
     users, pattern matching, or both. Once listed, you may list users
     on a channel or join it by double-clicking the channel name or
     selecting 'join channel' gadget.  Please note that this function
     can cause a high load of traffic and may take a while on slow
     (14.4 or less) connections.

@{b}Notify Window...@{ub}
     In the Notify window you may enter nicks of users that you wish to
     be notified of their entering/leaving IRC. The 'check period' is
     how often AmIRC will check for the specified users. Add a nick to
     the list by clicking in the input text gadget, and typing in the
     nick. Delete a nick by clicking on it's entry and then click on
     'Delete nick' gadget.

@{b}Favorite Channels...@{ub}
     In the Favorite Channels window you can make a list of all your
     favourite channels allowing you to join them with a simple double
     mouse-click.

@{b}DCC-Send Window...@{ub}
     Brings up the DCC-Send window where you can specify a user and a
     file to send to them. This window will also be opened
     automatically when using the 'DCC send' userbutton on the
     interface. 'Send Path' is the path (and filename) that will be sent
     to the user. Enter the name of the user in the textinput gadget at
     the bottom of the window. The cycle gadget next to the 'Nick'
     gadget selects either 'DCC Send' or 'DCC Move' protocols. See @{"DCC" Link "DCC"}
     section for details about these protocols.  The 'Reoffer' button
     allows you to reoffer a (failed) file to the user. The 'Remove Job'
     button will remove a complete transfer or if not complete, one
     click will abort the send and the second click will remove it.
     Finally, the 'Cleanup' button removes all finished or aborted
     transfers from the window.

@{b}DCC-Receive Window...@{ub}
     The DCC-Receive window is very similar to the DCC-Send window.
     This window will appear automatically on receiving a DCC request.
     The files will be downloaded to the path entered in the 'Receive
     Path' field. After a valid path is entered, click on an entry to
     receive, then click the 'Get' gadget at the bottom. You can also
     start the transfer by double-clicking on the entry or enabling
     'Auto accept DCC send requests' in the @{"User Modes" Link "User Modes"} menu.  If you
     are trying to receive after a failed send, you may use the
     'Resume' button instead of 'Get'. This will attempt to start
     transfer where it left off. If you wish to rename the incoming
     file for whatever reason, you may use the 'Rename' button.  The
     'Replace' button will cause the received file to replace any
     present versions.  'Remove Job' will abort an incoming file and
     remove a completed or aborted file.  'Cleanup' removes all
     finished or aborted transfers. See @{"DCC" Link "DCC"}.

@{b}DCC-Chat Window...@{ub}
     In the DCC-Chat window you can confirm a DCC chat connection from
     another user.  Simply select the client sending the request and
     click on 'Open' to make the connection.  You can close the
     connections using 'Close'. 'Cleanup' removes all closed DCC chat
     connections. See @{"DCC" Link "DCC"}.

@{b}Raw Log Window...@{ub}
     The Raw Log window can be used to view the raw IRC messages as
     they appear before AmIRC formats them for easy reading in the
     AmIRC listview.  Here you may also clear the log, and select when
     the log is active: 'Never', 'Only if window open', or 'Always'.
     The log Listview shows the USERHOST, Type of message, Channel
     Name, and message, in that order.

@{b}URL Grabber Window...@{ub}
     Any WWW URL AmIRC recognizes it will place in the URL Grabber
     window. From here you can select them and either send them to your
     browser or the clipboard. You can also clear the list.

@{b}Private Msgs Window...@{ub}
     The Private Messages window holds a history of private messages
     sent to you, which you can later reference or review. You can of
     course clear the list.

@{b}Info Message Window@{ub}
     The Info Messages window displays server messages, wallops
     messages, and CTCP requests.  Any 'Shanghai' gadgets that are
     activated will prevent that type of message from showing in the
     main channel window, even when the info window is closed.  The
     lower part of the window shows AmIRC's Lag-O-Meter. The VU style
     meter is a graphical representation of the current lag to the
     server. Next to the meter is the name of the server. Also shown
     are the current lag, last two probes and the average of the last
     two lags.

@{b}Flush Buffer@{ub}
     This item will clear the history of the main AmIRC listview.

@{b}Save Buffer...@{ub}
     This item allows you to select a filename to save the history
     buffer to disk.


@EndNode

@Node "User Modes" "AmIRC.guide/User Modes"
@Toc "Menus"

Menus
=====

User Modes Menu
---------------

@{b}Invisible?@{ub}
     Toggles wether you're invisible in the global userlist or not. See
     @{"IRC Terms" Link "IRC Terms"}.

@{b}Receive Wallops?@{ub}
     Toggles wether you will receive messages to all operators or not.
     See @{"IRC Terms" Link "IRC Terms"}.

@{b}Receive Server Notices?@{ub}
     Toggles wether you receive server notices or not.

@{b}Marked AWAY?@{ub}
     Marks you are AWAY.

@{b}Auto rejoin on KICK?@{ub}
     If set, will automatically attempt to reconnect you to a channel
     you have been kicked from. Note that if a ban was set with the
     kick, you will not be able to rejoin.

@{b}Auto reconnect to server?@{ub}
     If set, this will automatically attempt to reconnect you to the
     server if you are disconnected for any reason.

@{b}Clone detection@{ub}
     Detect wether clones are present.

@{b}Oper detection@{ub}
     Detect IRC Operators.

@{b}Auto open Dialog Windows?@{ub}
     If set, will automatically open chat window upon receipt of a @{"/MSG" Link "MSG"}
     or @{"DCC chat" Link "DCC"} request.

@{b}Auto accept DCC chat requests?@{ub}
     If set, this will automatically accept DCC chat requests.  It will
     not open a chat window for you, however. Do this by opening the
     DCC chat window in the Windows menu.

@{b}Auto accept DCC send requests?@{ub}
     If set, this will automatically accept DCC send requests, so
     downloading will start immediately.

@{b}Do BEEPs?@{ub}
     If set, AmIRC will send audio beeps (or samples, if configured in
     the @{"Events" Link "Events"} page of the settings requester) for certain events.

@{b}Play CTCP SOUND requests?@{ub}
     If checked, AmIRC will acknowledge and play @{"/CTCP" Link "CTCP"} sound requests,
     if this is configured properly.

@{b}Do Color codes?@{ub}
     Here you can enable the (in)famous @{"colour codes" Link "COLOURCODES"}.


@EndNode

@Node "Settings" "AmIRC.guide/Settings"
@Toc "Menus"

Menus
=====

Settings Menu
-------------

@{b}Setup...@{ub}
     Calls the @{"Setup window" Link "AmIRC Setup"}, allowing you to change the many settings of
     AmIRC to suit your needs.

@{b}MIMEPrefs...@{ub}
     Calls the MIMEPrefs program if present in the AmIRC directory or
     Prefs:. It allows you to set global MIME settings for view and
     saving files.

@{b}Dialog Window Buttons?@{ub}
     If set, the AmIRC dialogue window will contain 4 gadgets in the
     upper right corner.  These are labelled: 'Whois', 'Ping', 'DCC
     Chat', & 'DCC Send'.  These gadgets will perform their respective
     functions on the user that the dialogue window is opened to.

@{b}Use MIMEPrefs for viewing?@{ub}
     If set, AmIRC uses the global MIME settings set with the MIMEPrefs
     program to determine what program to view the received file with.

@{b}Use MIMEPrefs for saving?@{ub}
     If set, AmIRC uses the global MIME setting set with the MIMEPrefs
     program to determine whether and where to save the received file.

@{b}Use pages by default?@{ub}
     If set, AmIRC will only open one channel window at a time. If
     multiple channels are joined they can be accessed using the "tab"
     with the corresponding channelname at the top of the window.

@{b}Load Settings...@{ub}
     Opens a requester allowing you to recall previously saved
     non-default AmIRC Configurations.

@{b}Load settings from default@{ub}
     Reloads the last saved default configuration

@{b}Save Settings@{ub}
     Saves the current configuration under the last name set in the
     'Save settings as...' menu item.  If the settings have not
     previously been named, they are saved as default.

@{b}Save settings as...@{ub}
     Opens a requester allowing you to choose a filename to save the
     current AmIRC configuration as other than default.

@{b}Save as default@{ub}
     Saves the current AmIRC configuration as the default start-up
     configuration.

@{b}Create icons?@{ub}
     If Checked, will create icons for saved configuration files,
     allowing them to be selected from the Workbench.

@{b}Save Settings On Exit@{ub}
     If checked, this item will cause AmIRC to save the current
     settings as default upon exiting the program.

@{b}MUI Settings...@{ub}
     Opens the MUI Prefs program for altering the MUI Configurable AmIRC
     configuration.


@EndNode

@Node "Plugins" "AmIRC.guide/Plugins"
@Toc "Menus"

Menus
=====

Plugins Menu
------------

The Plugins menu shows a list of all installed AmIRC plugins. The
plugins are located in the Plugins directory in the AmIRC directory. It
also allows you to access any Plugin preference that may be available.


@EndNode

@Node "Rexx" "AmIRC.guide/Rexx"
@Toc "Menus"

Menus
=====

Rexx Menu
---------

This menu will only be present when any ARexx scripts reside in the
AmIRC/Rexx/ directory and will display them. AmIRC ARexx scripts should
be named with the .  amirx extension. From this menu you may execute
any existing AmIRC ARexx script.  See the full @{"ARexx guide" Link "ARexx"} for an
in-depth look on ARexx.


@EndNode

@Node "Commands" "AmIRC.guide/Commands"
@Next "Configuration"
@Prev "Menus"
@Toc "Main"

Using the commands in AmIRC.
****************************

Overview
========

AmIRC has many built-in commands. Some of these commands are processed
locally, whereas others are sent to the IRC server.

Commands generally start with a '/' to differentiate them from normal
text. If you want to use the / character at the start of normal text,
use '//' instead.

Many commands require a channel name as a parameter. AmIRC will
automatically fill in the channel name of the current window if you
don't specify a channel name on your own.

For commands which require a nick name (e.g. @{b}/MSG@{ub} or @{b}/OP@{ub}, there are
three special short-cut arguments:

@{b}.@{ub}
     The period is replaced with the nickname of the last person you
     have send a private message to.

@{b},@{ub}
     The comma is replaced with the nickname of the last person who
     send a message to you. Be careful with this, since you might
     easily address the wrong person if someone sends you a message
     while you are still typing this command!

@{b}:@{ub}
     The colon is replaced with the nickname of the last person which
     you have addressed with a @{b}'Nick:'@{ub} prefix inside a channel.

You may easily carry a dialogue with a particular user by first
clicking on their username in the user list, then any time you hit the
TAB key, the input string will be set up with '/MSG <user> ', after
which you may type in the message and hit return.  This will work after
initiating a @{"DCC Chat" Link "DCC"} request as well. Please note that if you have
configured the user list as a separate window, you must reactivate the
message window after clicking on a username.

You can also use TAB to complete a nickname by typing only the first
character, pressing TAB then will cycle you through all the nicks that
start with that character.

When you have set an @{"ALIAS" Link "ALIAS"} you can force AmIRC to use the original
command by preceding the command with an exlamation mark (!).

Reference to all AmIRC commands
===============================


 @{" ? " Link "?"}            Obtaining help on commands
 @{" ADMIN " Link "ADMIN"}        Showing the server's administrator
 @{" ALIAS " Link "ALIAS"}        Renaming a regularly used term
 @{" AWAY " Link "AWAY"}         Setting an AWAY message
 @{" BACK " Link "BACK"}         Resetting the AWAY state
 @{" BAN " Link "BAN"}          Banning users
 @{" BANDEL " Link "BANDEL"}       Removing a ban
 @{" BANLIST " Link "BANLIST"}      Listing bans
 @{" CHANNEL " Link "CHANNEL"}      Joining (or creating) a channel
 @{" CLEAR " Link "CLEAR"}        Clearing the buffer of a channel or nick
 @{" COLOURCODES " Link "COLOURCODES"}  Changing your message colours
 @{" CONNECT " Link "CONNECT"}      (Re)Connecting a server
 @{" CTCP " Link "CTCP"}         Sending commands to other people
 @{" CYCLE " Link "CYCLE"}        Automatically leave and rejoin a channel
 @{" DCC " Link "DCC"}          Making a direct connection
 @{" DESCRIBE " Link "DESCRIBE"}     Describing to a user
 @{" DEOP " Link "DEOP"}         Removing a user's Channel Op status
 @{" EXCADD " Link "EXCADD"}       Add ban exception(s) (IRCNet)
 @{" EXCDEL " Link "EXCDEL"}       Delete ban exception(s) (IRCNet)
 @{" EXCLIST " Link "EXCLIST"}      Show ban exceptions (IRCNet)
 @{" FAKE " Link "FAKE"}         Send fake servercommands to AmIRC
 @{" FINDHOST " Link "FINDHOST"}     Find users using a userhost pattern
 @{" GLINE " Link "GLINE"}        Showing list of banned domains
 @{" HELP " Link "HELP"}         Obtaining help on commands
 @{" HIGHLITE " Link "HIGHLITE"}     Highlighting text
 @{" HILITE " Link "HILITE"}       Highlighting text
 @{" IRCNAME " Link "IRCNAME"}      Changing your nickname
 @{" IGNORE " Link "IGNORE"}       Ignoring a user
 @{" INVADD " Link "INVADD"}       Add auto-invite(s) (IRCNet)
 @{" INVDEL " Link "INVDEL"}       Delete auto-invite(s) (IRCNet)
 @{" INVLIST " Link "INVLIST"}      Show auto-invite(s) (IRCNet)
 @{" INVITE " Link "INVITE"}       Inviting a user to a channel
 @{" INFO " Link "INFO"}         Showing server information
 @{" ISON " Link "ISON"}         Checking if a user is on IRC
 @{" JOIN " Link "JOIN"}         Joining (or creating) a channel
 @{" KICK " Link "KICK"}         Removing a user from a channel
 @{" KICKBAN " Link "KICKBAN"}      Removing and banning a user
 @{" KILL " Link "KILL"}         Disconnecting a user
 @{" LASTLOG " Link "LASTLOG"}      Searching the buffer
 @{" LEAVE " Link "LEAVE"}        Leaving a channel
 @{" LINKS " Link "LINKS"}        Showing server links
 @{" LIST " Link "LIST"}         Listing channels and their topics
 @{" LOAD " Link "LOAD"}         Forc AmIRC to load a plugin
 @{" LOG " Link "LOG"}          Logging a Chat Window
 @{" LUSERS " Link "LUSERS"}       Showing users information
 @{" M " Link "M"}            Sending a private message (PrivMsg)
 @{" MAP " Link "MAP"}          Showing a server map of the network
 @{" ME " Link "ME"}           Sending a CTCP Action to the channel
 @{" MODE " Link "MODE"}         Changing a Channel Mode
 @{" MOTD " Link "MOTD"}         Showing the Message Of The Day (MOTD)
 @{" MSG " Link "MSG"}          Sending a private message (PrivMsg)
 @{" NAMES " Link "NAMES"}        Getting a list of names
 @{" NICK " Link "NICK"}         Changing your nickname
 @{" NOTE " Link "NOTE"}         A look into the past
 @{" NOTICE " Link "NOTICE"}       Sending a notice to a user
 @{" NOTIFY " Link "NOTIFY"}       Notifying when a user is on IRC
 @{" OP " Link "OP"}           Setting Channel Operator status
 @{" OPER " Link "OPER"}         Becoming an IRC Operator
 @{" PART " Link "PART"}         Leaving a channel
 @{" PING " Link "PING"}         Sending a CTCP Ping
 @{" QKICK " Link "QKICK"}        Removing and banning a user
 @{" QKICKBAN " Link "QKICKBAN"}     Removing and banning a user
 @{" QUERY " Link "QUERY"}        Opening a Query window
 @{" QUIT " Link "QUIT"}         Ending an IRC session
 @{" QUOTE " Link "QUOTE"}        Sending unprocessed string to the server
 @{" RAW " Link "RAW"}          Sending unprocessed string to the server
 @{" RECONNECT " Link "RECONNECT"}    Reconnecting to the current server
 @{" REHASH " Link "REHASH"}       Restarting the server
 @{" RELOAD " Link "RELOAD"}       Force AmIRC to reload a plugin
 @{" RESTART " Link "RESTART"}      Restarting the server
 @{" RMSG " Link "RMSG"}         Sending a private message (PrivMsg)
 @{" RX " Link "RX"}           Starting an Arexx command
 @{" RXRETURN " Link "RXRETURN"}     Using Arexx to the fullest
 @{" SERVER " Link "SERVER"}       Connecting to a different server
 @{" SILENCE " Link "SILENCE"}      Silencing a user
 @{" SOUND " Link "SOUND"}        Sending sounds
 @{" SQUIT " Link "SQUIT"}        Quitting a server
 @{" STATS " Link "STATS"}        Showing the Stats
 @{" SUMMON " Link "SUMMON"}       Asking a user to come on IRC
 @{" TIME " Link "TIME"}         Query the current time of day
 @{" TOPIC " Link "TOPIC"}        Viewing or changing a channel's topic
 @{" TRACE " Link "TRACE"}        Tracing a user or a server
 @{" UMODE " Link "UMODE"}        Changing your own usermode
 @{" UNHIGHLITE " Link "UNHIGHLITE"}   Removing a Highlight entry
 @{" UNHILITE " Link "UNHILITE"}     Removing a Highlight entry
 @{" UNIGNORE " Link "UNIGNORE"}     Removing a user from the Ignore list
 @{" UNLOAD " Link "UNLOAD"}       Forc AmIRC to unload a plugin
 @{" UNVOICE " Link "UNVOICE"}      Removing a user's Voice
 @{" UPING " Link "UPING"}        Sending a Ping command
 @{" USERS " Link "USERS"}        Listing users on a server
 @{" USERHOST " Link "USERHOST"}     Getting USERHOST of a user
 @{" VERSION " Link "VERSION"}      Query the version of the server software
 @{" VOICE " Link "VOICE"}        Giving a user a Voice
 @{" WALLOPS " Link "WALLOPS"}      Writing to All Operators
 @{" WHO " Link "WHO"}          Global user pattern matching
 @{" WHOIS " Link "WHOIS"}        Get information about a user
 @{" WHOWAS " Link "WHOWAS"}       Get information on a nick no longer logged in


@EndNode

@Node "?" "AmIRC.guide/?"
@Toc "Commands"

Commands
========

?
-

Usage: @{b}/? [Command]@{ub}

With this command you can get a list of all available commands. When a
command is added behind it, you get the correct command syntax.

Alternative: @{"HELP" Link "HELP"}

EXAMPLES:

@{b}/?@{ub}
     Will show a list of all available commands

@{b}/? Ping@{ub}
     Will show the correct command syntax for the @{"PING" Link "PING"} command: @{i}Usage:
     /PING [nick]@{ui}


@EndNode

@Node "ADMIN" "AmIRC.guide/ADMIN"
@Toc "Commands"

Commands
========

ADMIN
-----

Usage: @{b}/ADMIN [Server]@{ub}

The admin message is used to find the name of the administrator of the
given server, or current server if [Server] parameter is omitted.

EXAMPLES:

@{b}/ADMIN irctest.vapor.com@{ub}
     Shows the information for the server @{i}irctest.vapor.com@{ui}:
          @{b}«Admin»@{ub} Administrative info about irctest.vapor.com
          @{b}«Admin»@{ub} Vapor's experimental ARCNet Server
          @{b}«Admin»@{ub} Oliver Wagner <owagner@vapor.com>
          @{b}«Admin»@{ub} Slow Mess Clients Welcome(tm)


@EndNode

@Node "ALIAS" "AmIRC.guide/ALIAS"
@Toc "Commands"

Commands
========

ALIAS
-----

Usage: @{b}/ALIAS [Alias [Replacement, %p for alias parameters]@{ub}

With ALIAS you can make an alias for frequently used terms. You can
also add parameters needed for certain commands using %p.

Special Note: When you have set an alias for a command that normally
exists in AmIRC, you can force AmIRC to use the original command
instead of the alias by preceding it with an exlamation mark.

You can also change Aliases using the @{"Alias Window" Link "Lists"}.  EXAMPLES:

@{b}/ALIAS Goto Join %p@{ub}
     You can now use: @{b}/GOTO #Test@{ub} instead of @{b}/JOIN #Test@{ub}

@{b}/!PING@{ub}
     Forces AmIRC to issue the original @{"PING" Link "PING"} command instead of an
     alias called PING.


@EndNode

@Node "AWAY" "AmIRC.guide/AWAY"
@Toc "Commands"

Commands
========

AWAY
----

Usage: @{b}/AWAY [message]@{ub}

When used with the optional [message] argument, it will mark you as
being away and send the message to any client sending a @{"MSG" Link "MSG"} to you.
Otherwise, it will remove a previously set away message.

Related: @{"BACK" Link "BACK"}

EXAMPLES:

@{b}/AWAY eating dinner@{ub}
     Will send the message @{i}'<nick> is away: eating dinner'@{ui}, where nick
     is the nickname of the user that is away.

@{b}/AWAY@{ub}
     Will remove a previously set Away Message.


@EndNode

@Node "BACK" "AmIRC.guide/BACK"
@Toc "Commands"

Commands
========

BACK
----

Usage: @{b}/BACK (no arguments)@{ub}

Where @{"AWAY" Link "AWAY"} toggles between setting and resetting the Away state.  This
command always resets the Away state and thus no longer marks you as
away.

Related: @{"AWAY" Link "AWAY"}

EXAMPLES:

@{b}/BACK@{ub}
     Will reset the away state and no longer marks you as away.


@EndNode

@Node "BAN" "AmIRC.guide/BAN"
@Toc "Commands"

Commands
========

BAN
---

Usage: @{b}/BAN [channel] userhost[,userhost...]@{ub}

This command will ban everyone with the specified userhost(s) from
entering the channel. With the optional channel argument you can setup
a ban on a different channel than the one in which window the command
is executed.

Related: @{"BANDEL" Link "BANDEL"} @{"BANLIST" Link "BANLIST"} @{"KICK" Link "KICK"} @{"KICKBAN" Link "KICKBAN"} @{"QKICK" Link "QKICK"} @{"QKICKBAN" Link "QKICKBAN"}

EXAMPLES:

@{b}/BAN bill@*.microsoft.com@{ub}
     Will prevent a user called @{i}bill@{ui} in the @{i}microsoft.com@{ui} domain from
     entering the channel.

@{b}/BAN Amiga bill@*.microsoft.com@{ub}
     Will ban user @{i}bill@{ui} on @{i}microsoft.com@{ui} from entering @{i}#Amiga@{ui}.


@EndNode

@Node "BANDEL" "AmIRC.guide/BANDEL"
@Toc "Commands"

Commands
========

BANDEL
------

Usage: @{b}/BANDEL [channel] userhost[,userhost...]@{ub}

Will remove a ban on the specified userhost(s) on the (optional)
channel.

Related: @{"BAN" Link "BAN"} @{"BANLIST" Link "BANLIST"} @{"KICK" Link "KICK"} @{"KICKBAN" Link "KICKBAN"} @{"QKICK" Link "QKICK"} @{"QKICKBAN" Link "QKICKBAN"}

EXAMPLES:

@{b}/BANDEL *!*@*microsoft.com@{ub}
     Will remove the ban for the @{i}microsoft.com@{ui} domain.


@EndNode

@Node "BANLIST" "AmIRC.guide/BANLIST"
@Toc "Commands"

Commands
========

BANLIST
-------

Usage: @{b}/BANLIST [channel] userhost[,userhost...]@{ub}

Shows a list of bans currently active on the (specified) channel.

Related: @{"BAN" Link "BAN"} @{"BANDEL" Link "BANDEL"} @{"KICK" Link "KICK"} @{"KICKBAN" Link "KICKBAN"} @{"QKICK" Link "QKICK"} @{"QKICKBAN" Link "QKICKBAN"}

EXAMPLES:

@{b}/BANLIST@{ub}
     Shows a list of all bans on the currently active channel.


@EndNode

@Node "CHANNEL" "AmIRC.guide/CHANNEL"
@Toc "Commands"

Commands
========

CHANNEL
-------

Usage: @{b}/CHANNEL channel[,channel[,...]] [key[,key,...]]@{ub}

Join a channel on the IRC. If the channel doesn't exists, it is
automatically created.

There are two kinds of channels: Channel names starting with an @{i}#@{ui} are
global channels and available on all IRC servers which are connected to
the net you are currently on. Channels which begin with @{i}&@{ui} are local to
the chat server you are connected to.

If a channel requires a special keyword to join, you can submit this
after the channel name.

AmIRC will look for a channel window which isn't currently bound to a
channel. If it doesn't find one, a new window will be created and bound
to this channel.

Alternative: @{"JOIN" Link "JOIN"}

Related: @{"CYCLE" Link "CYCLE"} @{"LEAVE" Link "LEAVE"} @{"PART" Link "PART"} @{"QUIT" Link "QUIT"}

EXAMPLES:

@{b}/CHANNEL #Amiga@{ub}
     Join the channel @{i}#Amiga@{ui}

@{b}/CHANNEL #Amiga,#AmIRC@{ub}
     Join the channels @{i}#Amiga@{ui} and @{i}#AmIRC@{ui}

@{b}/CHANNEL #Secret Booh@{ub}
     Join the channel @{i}#Secret@{ui} that protected with keyword @{i}Booh@{ui}.


@EndNode

@Node "CLEAR" "AmIRC.guide/CLEAR"
@Toc "Commands"

Commands
========

CLEAR
-----

Usage: @{b}/CLEAR [channel|nick]@{ub}

With this command to can clear the buffer of a channel or Query window.
If no channel name or nick is specified the buffer of the window in
which the command was issued will be cleared.  Be warned that any text
in the buffer will be gone permanently!

EXAMPLES:

@{b}/Clear #Throat@{ub}
     Will clear the buffer of the channel @{i}#Throat@{ui}.


@EndNode

@Node "COLOURCODES" "AmIRC.guide/COLOURCODES"
@Toc "Commands"

Commands
========

COLOURCODES
-----------

Usage: @{b}Ctrl-C [Text Colour],[Background Colour]@{ub}

Please note that this feature is not really a command, but it can be
used to control the colour(s) in which a (public) text appears. Both
the text and the background colour can be changed by first pressing
Ctrl^C (That's the 'Ctrl' key + the 'C' key simultaneously!). followed
by either one (for the text colour) or two values (text and
background). In most fonts Ctrl^C is displayed as a box (unknown
character). You can have multiple colour changes in a single text, all
preceded by Ctrl^C.  Here's a list of available colours and their
respective values:

      Value:   Colour:      RGB Values:
     
        0*     White        255 255 255
        1      Black        000 000 000
        2      Navy         000 000 139
        3      Green        000 255 000
        4      Red          255 000 000
        5      Maroon       139 000 000
        6      Purple       160 032 240
        7      Orange       255 165 000
        8      Yellow       255 255 000
        9      Lime         050 205 050
       10      Teal         128 128 128
       11      Aqua         127 255 212
       12      Blue         000 000 255
       13      Fuchsia      255 192 205
       14      Grey         190 190 190
       15      Silver       211 211 211
     
       *Please note that background colour 0 is
        the standard list background colour.

EXAMPLES: ([CTRL^C] indicates pressing CTRL and C simultaneously)

@{b}This text is [CTRL^C]4 RED.@{ub}
     When this line is sent to a channel the word @{i}RED@{ui} will be displayed
     in..... red.

@{b}I like [CTRL^C]8,1 Colours [CTRL^C]1,0 a lot.@{ub}
     Here the word @{i}Colours@{ui} will be Yellow on a Black background.


@EndNode

@Node "CONNECT" "AmIRC.guide/CONNECT"
@Toc "Commands"

Commands
========

CONNECT
-------

Usage: @{b}/CONNECT server [port [remote server]]@{ub}

The CONNECT command can be used to force a server to try to establish a
new connection to another server immediately. CONNECT is a privileged
command and is available only to IRC Operators. If a [remote server] is
given then the CONNECT attempt is made by that remote server to the
given server and port.

EXAMPLES:

@{b}/CONNECT test1.irc.com@{ub}
     Will connect @{i}test1.irc.com@{ui} to the currently connected server


@EndNode

@Node "CTCP" "AmIRC.guide/CTCP"
@Toc "Commands"

Commands
========

CTCP
----

Usage: @{b}/CTCP nick request@{ub}

CTCP or @{i}Client To Client Protocol@{ui} is a standard for sending commands to
other clients on IRC. Basically, CTCP messages are simply private
messages that include a code to alert the receiving client (not user)
to respond to the command.

CTCP commands are typically used to get information from the receiving
client, such as '/CTCP time', or '/CTCP version'. Even @{"DCC" Link "DCC"} sends a
request via CTCP to the receiving client, asking to initiate a direct
connection.

Related: @{"ME" Link "ME"} @{"DCC" Link "DCC"} @{"SOUND" Link "SOUND"} @{"TIME" Link "TIME"} @{"QUERY" Link "QUERY"} @{"VERSION" Link "VERSION"}

EXAMPLES:

@{b}/CTCP Franky Version@{ub}
     This will return the version of Franky's client:
          @{b}«Reply»@{ub} Franky VERSION AmIRC/AmigaOS 1.118 by Oliver Wagner <owagner@vapor.com> :
                  http://www.vapor.com/amirc/ : [#00000000] : This space for rent.
                  Mail <ads@vapor.com> for more info.

@{b}/CTCP Bert Time@{ub}
     This will show the time set on Bert's machine:
          @{b}«Reply»@{ub} Bert TIME Tue Jan 13 10:54:23 1998


@EndNode

@Node "CYCLE" "AmIRC.guide/CYCLE"
@Toc "Commands"

Commands
========

CYCLE
-----

Usage: @{b}/CYCLE [channel]@{ub}

With CYCLE you can make AmIRC automatically leave and join a
(specified) channel.  This can be useful when you want to check a
changed user mode on a channel. When no channel name is given, the
currently active channel will be 'cycled'.

Related: @{"CHANNEL" Link "CHANNEL"} @{"JOIN" Link "JOIN"} @{"LEAVE" Link "LEAVE"} @{"PART" Link "PART"}

EXAMPLES:

@{b}/CYCLE@{ub}
     Will make AmIRC leave and join the currently active channel.

@{b}/CTCP #Amiga@{ub}
     Will make AmIRC leave and join #Amiga, no matter what channel is
     active.
          @{b}«Reply»@{ub} Bert TIME Tue Jan 13 10:54:23 1998


@EndNode

@Node "DCC" "AmIRC.guide/DCC"
@Toc "Commands"

Commands
========

DCC
---

Usage: @{b}/DCC [SEND|MOVE|CHAT|SCHAT|GET|RESUME|LIST] [nick] [parameters]@{ub}
 or: @{b}/DCC CLOSE [SEND|GET|CHAT|SCHAT] nick [parameters]@{ub}

DCC or @{i}Direct Client Connection@{ui} is a protocol that IRC clients can use
to communicate directly with each other, bypassing the IRC server.  The
reason for this is to form a faster, more stable and direct connection
through which users can transfer files, or send private messages.

Note that AmIRC has its own set of Highly Optimized DCC protocols
built-in, and does not require external DCC utilities.

The most common use of DCC is for transferring files between two
clients.  The initiating client will send a message through the IRC
server, telling the receiver that a connection is requested. At this
time, the receiver will either accept or reject the offer for the
connection. If the receiver accepts the connection, the initiating
client will proceed to send the information directly to the receiver.
If the connection is refused, the initiating client will simply
time-out the attempt to connect.

Another use of the DCC standard is DCC chat, which, like DCC Send, will
send a CTCP request to the receiving client to set up a direct link. In
this case, however, the purpose of the link is for users to send
messages to each other. Because the messages are sent through the
direct link, and do not pass through the IRC server, this method of
sending messages is much more private than using the IRC's private
message (@{"MSG" Link "MSG"}) command.  With AmiRC, it must be noted that a DCC Chat
request will not open a dialogue window for you, instead, when DCC chat
is initiated and accepted, all privmsg's (@{"MSG" Link "MSG"}) to the receiving user
will be sent through the DCC link. If you wish to have a dialogue box
for chatting, the best way to do this is to highlight the users's name
in the userlist by clicking on it and then click on the 'Query' button
below the listview. This will open a window that has several options
within it. From here, you can @{"PING" Link "PING"} or @{"WHOIS" Link "WHOIS"} the other user, or you may
initiate a @{i}'DCC Send'@{ui} or @{i}'DCC Chat'@{ui}. Starting a @{i}'DCC Chat'@{ui} from this
window will allow you to carry on a dialogue with the remote user
through the window.

EXAMPLES:

@{b}/DCC send Franky AmIRC20.lzx@{ub}
     Will send a request to @{i}Franky@{ui} to transfer a file called
     @{i}AmIRC20.lzx@{ui}.  When Franky (auto-)accepts transfer will begin.

@{b}/DCC move Franky AmIRC20.lzx@{ub}
     Will basically do the same as 'DCC Send' but it is capable of
     resuming an aborted or failed transfer. It looks in the receiving
     directory and if a file with the same name if found it will send a
     'DCC Resume' instead of 'DCC Send'.


@EndNode

@Node "DESCRIBE" "AmIRC.guide/DESCRIBE"
@Toc "Commands"

Commands
========

DESCRIBE
--------

Usage: @{b}/DESCRIBE nick describe-text@{ub}

DESCRIBE is used to 'describe' something to another user.

Related: @{"ME" Link "ME"} @{"MSG" Link "MSG"}

EXAMPLES:

@{b}/DESCRIBE John It is nice weather here@{ub}
     Send the following text to user @{i}John@{ui}:
          @{b}«Describe»@{ub} <nick> It is nice weather here
     Where <nick> is your nickname.


@EndNode

@Node "DEOP" "AmIRC.guide/DEOP"
@Toc "Commands"

Commands
========

DEOP
----

Usage: @{b}/DEOP [channel] nick[,nick...]@{ub}

Will remove the Channel Operator status of one or several users. Note
that the user issuing the command needs to be Channel Operator himself.

Related: @{"OP" Link "OP"}

EXAMPLES:

@{b}/DEOP Billy@{ub}
     Removes Channel Operator status from a user called @{i}Billy@{ui}.

@{b}/DEOP #Amiga Billy,John@{ub}
     Removes Channel Operator status from users @{i}Billy@{ui} and @{i}John@{ui} on the
     channel @{i}#Amiga@{ui}.


@EndNode

@Node "EXCADD" "AmIRC.guide/EXCADD"
@Toc "Commands"

Commands
========

EXCADD
------

Usage: @{b}/EXCADD [channel] userhost[,userhost...]@{ub}

With this (IRCNet specific!) command you can add exceptions to your @{"ban" Link "BAN"}.
This way you can prevent a (friendly) user from being banned by you.
With the optional channel argument you can setup an exception for a
different channel than the one in which window the command is executed.

Related: @{"BAN" Link "BAN"} @{"BANDEL" Link "BANDEL"} @{"BANLIST" Link "BANLIST"} @{"EXCDEL" Link "EXCDEL"} @{"EXCLIST" Link "EXCLIST"} @{"KICK" Link "KICK"}          @{"KICKBAN" Link "KICKBAN"} @{"QKICK" Link "QKICK"}
@{"QKICKBAN" Link "QKICKBAN"}

EXAMPLES:

@{b}/EXCADD bill@*.microsoft.com@{ub}
     Will add a user called @{i}bill@{ui} in the @{i}microsoft.com@{ui} domain to your ban
     exceptions, preventing you from banning him.

@{b}/EXCADD Amiga bill@*.microsoft.com@{ub}
     Will prevent user @{i}bill@{ui} on @{i}microsoft.com@{ui} from being banned on
     @{i}#Amiga@{ui}.


@EndNode

@Node "EXCDEL" "AmIRC.guide/EXCDEL"
@Toc "Commands"

Commands
========

EXCDEL
------

Usage: @{b}/EXCDEL [channel] userhost[,userhost...]@{ub}

With this (IRCNet specific!) command you can delete exceptions to your
@{"ban" Link "BAN"}.  With the optional channel argument you can remove an exception
for a different channel than the one in which window the command is
executed.

Related: @{"BAN" Link "BAN"} @{"BANDEL" Link "BANDEL"} @{"BANLIST" Link "BANLIST"} @{"EXCADD" Link "EXCADD"} @{"EXCLIST" Link "EXCLIST"} @{"KICK" Link "KICK"}          @{"KICKBAN" Link "KICKBAN"} @{"QKICK" Link "QKICK"}
@{"QKICKBAN" Link "QKICKBAN"}

EXAMPLES:

@{b}/EXCDEL bill@*.microsoft.com@{ub}
     Removes a user called @{i}bill@{ui} in the @{i}microsoft.com@{ui} domain from your
     ban exceptions, allowing you from banning him again.

@{b}/EXCDEL Amiga bill@*.microsoft.com@{ub}
     Allows you to ban user @{i}bill@{ui} on @{i}microsoft.com@{ui} on @{i}#Amiga@{ui} again.


@EndNode

@Node "EXCLIST" "AmIRC.guide/EXCLIST"
@Toc "Commands"

Commands
========

EXCLIST
-------

Usage: @{b}/EXLIST [channel]@{ub}

This (IRCNet specific!) command shows you all domains that are excluded
from your @{"bans" Link "BAN"}.  With the optional channel argument you can view an
exceptions list for a different channel than the one in which window
the command is executed.

Related: @{"BAN" Link "BAN"} @{"BANDEL" Link "BANDEL"} @{"BANLIST" Link "BANLIST"} @{"EXCADD" Link "EXCADD"} @{"EXCDEL" Link "EXCDEL"} @{"KICK" Link "KICK"}          @{"KICKBAN" Link "KICKBAN"} @{"QKICK" Link "QKICK"}
@{"QKICKBAN" Link "QKICKBAN"}

EXAMPLES:

@{b}/EXCLIST@{ub}
     Will show a list of all userhosts that are excluded from banning
     on the currently active channel.

@{b}/EXCLIST Amiga@{ub}
     Will show a list of all userhosts that are excluded from banning
     on @{i}#Amiga@{ui}.


@EndNode

@Node "FAKE" "AmIRC.guide/FAKE"
@Toc "Commands"

Commands
========

FAKE
----

Usage: @{b}/FAKE server_data@{ub}

With this command you can fake data that a server normally sends to
AmIRC. This is mainly useful for debugging purposes when, for instance,
writing a script. This way you will be able to test AmIRC's reaction on
certain incoming data from a server.  WARNING: This command can result
in AmIRC crashing very easily when not used properly!  Do not use this
command unless you are absolutely sure what you're doing.

EXAMPLES:

@{b}/FAKE :Bill!Boss@Microsoft.com JOIN #LameOS@{ub}
     Will result in AmIRC reporting that: -> Bill(Boss@Microsoft.com)
     has joined channel #LameOS

@{b}/FAKE :Bill PRIVMSG #LameOS Anyone got pie for me?@{ub}
     Will show the following in the channel window of #LameOS: Bill |
     Anyone got pie for me?


@EndNode

@Node "FINDHOST" "AmIRC.guide/FINDHOST"
@Toc "Commands"

Commands
========

FINDHOST
--------

Usage: @{b}/FINDHOST [channel|ALL] userhost@{ub}

With this command you can search for a user using a userhost pattern.
AmIRC will return all users matching the pattern on the currently
active channel. Alternatively you can specify which channel will be
searched in. With the ALL argument you can search the entire network.

Related: @{"USERS" Link "USERS"} @{"USERHOST" Link "USERHOST"} @{"WHO" Link "WHO"}

EXAMPLES:

@{b}/FINDHOST *.vapor.com@{ub}
     Will list all users at the @{i}vapor.com@{ui} domain on the currently
     active channel.

@{b}/FINDHOST #Amiga *.vapor.com@{ub}
     Shows all users at the @{i}vapor.com@{ui} domain on @{i}#Amiga@{ui}.

@{b}/FINDHOST all *.com@{ub}
     Shows all users at the @{i}.com@{ui} domain on the network.


@EndNode

@Node "GLINE" "AmIRC.guide/GLINE"
@Toc "Commands"

Commands
========

GLINE
-----

Usage: @{b}/GLINE [gline]@{ub}

GLINE returns a list of all (partial) domains that are banned from the
network.  The optional parameter is used as a mask.

EXAMPLES:

@{b}/GLINE@{ub}
     Returns all domains banned from the network.


@EndNode

@Node "HELP" "AmIRC.guide/HELP"
@Toc "Commands"

Commands
========

HELP
----

Usage: @{b}/HELP [Command]@{ub}

With this command you can get a list of all available commands. When
the optional command parameter you get specific help about that command.

Alternative: @{"?" Link "?"}

EXAMPLES:

@{b}/HELP@{ub}
     Will show a list of all available commands

@{b}/HELP Ping@{ub}
     Will show additional help about the @{"PING" Link "PING"} command.


@EndNode

@Node "HIGHLITE" "AmIRC.guide/HIGHLITE"
@Toc "Commands"

Commands
========

HIGHLITE
--------

Usage: @{b}/HIGHLITE [item]@{ub}

HIGHLITE can be used to light up certain texts. They will be shown in a
colour that's defined in the @{"Settings" Link "Colors"}.

You can also change Highlighting using the @{"Hilight Window" Link "Lists"}.

Alternative: @{"HILITE" Link "HILITE"}

Related: @{"UNHIGHLITE" Link "UNHIGHLITE"} @{"UNHILITE" Link "UNHILITE"}

EXAMPLES:

@{b}/HIGHLITE MyName@{ub}
     Whenever AmIRC encounters @{i}MyName@{ui} it will be shown in the Hilighted
     colour.


@EndNode

@Node "HILITE" "AmIRC.guide/HILITE"
@Toc "Commands"

Commands
========

HILITE
------

Usage: @{b}/HILITE [item]@{ub}

HIGHLITE can be used to light up certain texts. They will be shown in a
colour that's defined in the @{"Settings" Link "Colors"}.

You can also change Highlighting using the @{"Hilight Window" Link "Lists"}.
Alternative: @{"HIGHLITE" Link "HIGHLITE"}

Related: @{"UNHIGHLITE" Link "UNHIGHLITE"} @{"UNHILITE" Link "UNHILITE"}

EXAMPLES:

@{b}/HILITE MyName@{ub}
     Whenever AmIRC encounters @{i}MyName@{ui} it will be shown in the Hilighted
     colour.


@EndNode

@Node "IRCNAME" "AmIRC.guide/IRCNAME"
@Toc "Commands"

Commands
========

IRCNAME
-------

Usage: @{b}/IRCNAME [new name]@{ub}

IRCNAME is used to give yourself a nickname or change your current one.
If the chosen nick is already in use, you will be notified of this and
prompted for a new nick.

Alternative: @{"NICK" Link "NICK"}

EXAMPLES:

@{b}/IRCNAME Phalanx@{ub}
     Sets your nickname to 'Phalanx'


@EndNode

@Node "IGNORE" "AmIRC.guide/IGNORE"
@Toc "Commands"

Commands
========

IGNORE
------

Usage: @{b}/IGNORE [userhost|nick [[+|-]TEXT [+|-]PRIV [+|- -]CTCP
[+|-]ALL]]@{ub}

IGNORE can be used to ignore messages coming from an annoying user. You
can set different levels of ignoring:

     text - This will block only text.
     priv - This will block all private messages.
     ctcp - You won't receive any CTCP request.
     all  - All traffic will be blocked.

Related: @{"SILENCE" Link "SILENCE"} @{"UNIGNORE" Link "UNIGNORE"}

EXAMPLES:

@{b}/IGNORE bill@user1.microsoft.com +priv@{ub}
     This will ignore all PrivMsgs (@{"MSG" Link "MSG"}) sent by the offending user.

@{b}/IGNORE Bill -ctcp@{ub}
     Removes CTCP ignores of @{i}Bill@{ui}


@EndNode

@Node "INVADD" "AmIRC.guide/INVADD"
@Toc "Commands"

Commands
========

INVADD
------

Usage: @{b}/INVADD [channel] userhost[,userhost...]@{ub}

With this (IRCNet specific!) command you can add users to your
auto-invite list.  This way you automatically @{"invite" Link "INVITE"} them to a
(specified) channel whenever they log onto IRCNet. With the optional
channel argument you can setup an auto-invite for a different channel
than the one in which window the command is executed.

Related: @{"INVDEL" Link "INVDEL"} @{"INVLIST" Link "INVLIST"} @{"INVITE" Link "INVITE"}

EXAMPLES:

@{b}/INVADD bill@*.microsoft.com@{ub}
     Will add a user called @{i}bill@{ui} in the @{i}microsoft.com@{ui} domain to your
     auto-invite list causing you to automatically invite him when he
     logs on.

@{b}/INVADD Amiga bill@*.microsoft.com@{ub}
     Will make you auto-invite user @{i}bill@{ui} on @{i}microsoft.com@{ui} to @{i}#Amiga@{ui}.


@EndNode

@Node "INVDEL" "AmIRC.guide/INVDEL"
@Toc "Commands"

Commands
========

INVDEL
------

Usage: @{b}/INVDEL [channel] userhost[,userhost...]@{ub}

With this (IRCNet specific!) command you can remove users from your
auto-invite list.  With the optional channel argument you can remove an
auto-invite for a different channel than the one in which window the
command is executed.

Related: @{"INVADD" Link "INVADD"} @{"INVLIST" Link "INVLIST"} @{"INVITE" Link "INVITE"}

EXAMPLES:

@{b}/INVDEL bill@*.microsoft.com@{ub}
     Removes a user called @{i}bill@{ui} in the @{i}microsoft.com@{ui} domain from your
     auto-invite list.

@{b}/INVDEL Amiga bill@*.microsoft.com@{ub}
     Stops you from auto-inviting user @{i}bill@{ui} on @{i}microsoft.com@{ui} to @{i}#Amiga@{ui}.


@EndNode

@Node "INVLIST" "AmIRC.guide/INVLIST"
@Toc "Commands"

Commands
========

INVLIST
-------

Usage: @{b}/INVLIST [channel]@{ub}

This (IRCNet specific!) command shows you all domains that are
automatically @{"invited" Link "INVITE"} to the (specified) channel. With the optional
channel argument you can view the auto-invites for a specific channel.

Related: @{"INVADD" Link "INVADD"} @{"INVDEL" Link "INVDEL"} @{"INVITE" Link "INVITE"}

EXAMPLES:

@{b}/INVLIST@{ub}
     Will show a list of all userhosts that are automatically invited
     to the currently active channel.

@{b}/INVLIST Amiga@{ub}
     Will show a list of all userhosts that are automatically invited
     to @{i}#Amiga@{ui}.


@EndNode

@Node "INVITE" "AmIRC.guide/INVITE"
@Toc "Commands"

Commands
========

INVITE
------

Usage: @{b}/INVITE [channel] nick@{ub}

Invites a user to the channel given in the argument, regardless of
wether the channel exists. If the named channel is @{"invite only(+i)" Link "MODE"}, the
user performing the command must be a channel operator for that
channel. When receiving an invitation you will be presented with a
requester.

Related: @{"INVADD" Link "INVADD"} @{"INVDEL" Link "INVDEL"} @{"INVLIST" Link "INVLIST"}

EXAMPLES:

@{b}/INVITE freddie #AmIRC@{ub}
     Invites 'freddie' to join @{i}#AmIRC@{ui}.


@EndNode

@Node "INFO" "AmIRC.guide/INFO"
@Toc "Commands"

Commands
========

INFO
----

Usage: @{b}/INFO [server]@{ub}

The INFO command is required to return information which describes the
server: its version, when it was compiled, the patch level, when it was
started, and any other miscellaneous information which may be
considered to be relevant. If no parameter is submitted the currently
connected server will be shown.

EXAMPLES:

@{b}/INFO@{ub}
     Will return information about the server the user is currently
     connected to.


@EndNode

@Node "ISON" "AmIRC.guide/ISON"
@Toc "Commands"

Commands
========

ISON
----

Usage: @{b}/ISON nick [nick [nick [...]]]@{ub}

Quickly returns the user's nick if it is found, does nothing if it is
not.

Related: @{"WHOIS" Link "WHOIS"} @{"WHOWAS" Link "WHOWAS"} @{"WHO" Link "WHO"}

EXAMPLES:

@{b}/ISON Kenneth@{ub}
     Returns: '@{b}<ISON>@{ub}Kenneth', if nick 'Kenneth' is found on the server.


@EndNode

@Node "JOIN" "AmIRC.guide/JOIN"
@Toc "Commands"

Commands
========

JOIN
----

Usage: @{b}/JOIN channel[,channel[,...]] [key[,key[,...]]]@{ub}

Join a channel on the IRC. If the channel doesn't exists, it is
automatically created.

There are two kinds of channels: Channel names starting with an @{i}#@{ui} are
global channels and available on all IRC servers which are connected to
the net you are currently on. Channels which begin with @{i}&@{ui} are local to
the chat server you are connected to.

If a channel requires a special keyword to join, you can submit this
after the channel name.

AmIRC will look for a channel window which isn't currently bound to a
channel. If it doesn't find one, a new window will be created and bound
to this channel.

Alternative: @{"CHANNEL" Link "CHANNEL"}

Related: @{"CYCLE" Link "CYCLE"} @{"LEAVE" Link "LEAVE"} @{"PART" Link "PART"} @{"QUIT" Link "QUIT"}

EXAMPLES:

@{b}/JOIN #Amiga@{ub}
     Join channel @{i}#Amiga@{ui}

@{b}/JOIN #Amiga,#AmIRC@{ub}
     Join channels @{i}#Amiga@{ui} and @{i}#AmIRC@{ui}

@{b}/JOIN #Secret Booh@{ub}
     Join channel @{i}#Secret@{ui} with keyword @{i}Booh@{ui}.


@EndNode

@Node "KICK" "AmIRC.guide/KICK"
@Toc "Commands"

Commands
========

KICK
----

Usage: @{b}/KICK [channel] nick [reason]@{ub}

Forcibly removes a user from the named channel. The user sending the
/KICK command must be a Channel Operator of the channel. If the optional
[reason] is given, it will be shown as the reason for the kick.

Related: @{"BAN" Link "BAN"} @{"BANDEL" Link "BANDEL"} @{"BANLIST" Link "BANLIST"} @{"KICKBAN" Link "KICKBAN"} @{"QKICK" Link "QKICK"} @{"QKICKBAN" Link "QKICKBAN"}

EXAMPLES:

@{b}/KICK #AmIRC Freddie Take it outside!@{ub}
     Forces 'Freddie' from channel @{i}#AmIRC@{ui} with the reason 'Take it
     outside!'.


@EndNode

@Node "KICKBAN" "AmIRC.guide/KICKBAN"
@Toc "Commands"

Commands
========

KICKBAN
-------

Usage: @{b}/KICKBAN [channel] nick [reason]@{ub}

Forcibly removes a user from the named channel and prevents him from
re-entering with a ban. The user sending the /KICKBAN command must be a
channel operator of the channel. If the optional [reason] is given, it
will be shown as the reason for the kick & ban.

Related: @{"BAN" Link "BAN"} @{"BANDEL" Link "BANDEL"} @{"BANLIST" Link "BANLIST"} @{"KICK" Link "KICK"} @{"QKICK" Link "QKICK"} @{"QKICKBAN" Link "QKICKBAN"}

EXAMPLES:

@{b}/KICKBAN #AmIRC Freddie You dirty pirate!@{ub}
     Forces 'Freddie' from channel @{i}#AmIRC@{ui} with the reason @{i}'You dirty
     pirate!'@{ui} and cannot re-enter because he's banned.


@EndNode

@Node "KILL" "AmIRC.guide/KILL"
@Toc "Commands"

Commands
========

KILL
----

Usage: @{b}Usage: /KILL nick comment@{ub}

This command allows IRC Operators to disconnect abusive users from the
network.

EXAMPLES:

@{b}/KILL Pierat You're not wanted here!@{ub}
     Disconnects user @{i}Pierat@{ui} with the reason @{i}'You're not wanted here!'@{ui}


@EndNode

@Node "LASTLOG" "AmIRC.guide/LASTLOG"
@Toc "Commands"

Commands
========

LASTLOG
-------

Usage @{b}/LASTLOG [undefined]@{ub}

Searches back through AmIRC's buffer and displays all occurrences of the
specified text.

EXAMPLES:

@{b}/LASTLOG amirc@{ub}
     Searches and displays all lines from the buffer containing the
     text @{i}'amirc'@{ui}.


@EndNode

@Node "LEAVE" "AmIRC.guide/LEAVE"
@Toc "Commands"

Commands
========

LEAVE
-----

Usage: @{b}/LEAVE [Channel[,Channel[,...]]@{ub}

Leaves a channel. If you don't give a channel name as a parameter, the
channel currently bound to the window in which in the command is
entered will be left.

Alternative: @{"PART" Link "PART"}

Related: @{"CHANNEL" Link "CHANNEL"} @{"CYCLE" Link "CYCLE"} @{"JOIN" Link "JOIN"}

EXAMPLES:

@{b}/LEAVE@{ub}
     Leave the channel currently bound to this window.

@{b}/LEAVE #AmigaGER@{ub}
     Leave channel @{i}#AmigaGER@{ui}.


@EndNode

@Node "LINKS" "AmIRC.guide/LINKS"
@Toc "Commands"

Commands
========

LINKS
-----

Usage: @{b}/LINKS [pattern]@{ub}

LINKS shows which server of the IRC network is connected to which other
server. The optional [pattern] can be used to limit the shown server
with a mask.

Related: @{"MAP" Link "MAP"}

EXAMPLES:

@{b}/LINKS *.*com@{ub}
     Shows all links with servers ending with .com


@EndNode

@Node "LIST" "AmIRC.guide/LIST"
@Toc "Commands"

Commands
========

LIST
----

Usage: @{b}/LIST [pattern] [MIN minusers]@{ub}

Shows the @{"Channel List window" Link "Windows"} in which the accessible channels are
listed. The optional [pattern] is used as a mask and the @{i}MIN minusers@{ui}
parameter prevents channels with less users to be displayed.

EXAMPLES:

@{b}/LIST@{ub}
     Returns a list of all public channels on available. Note that
     'secret' channels are only shown when the user has actually joined
     them.

@{b}/LIST br* 6@{ub}
     Returns all channels starting with @{i}br@{ui} and minimal 6 users present.


@EndNode

@Node "LOAD" "AmIRC.guide/LOAD"
@Toc "Commands"

Commands
========

LOAD
----

Usage: @{b}/LOAD plugin@{ub}

With this command you can force AmIRC to load a certain plugin that has
been installed after AmIRC was started.

Related: @{"RELOAD" Link "RELOAD"} @{"UNLOAD" Link "UNLOAD"}

EXAMPLES:
@{b}/LOAD XDCC@{ub}
     Forces AmIRC to load the XDCC plugin


@EndNode

@Node "LOG" "AmIRC.guide/LOG"
@Toc "Commands"

Commands
========

LOG
---

Usage: @{b}/LOG [filename|ON|OFF]@{ub}

LOG allows you to start/stop logging, as well as setting the log
filename and displaying status of logging.

EXAMPLES:

@{b}/LOG@{ub}
     Displays current status of logging

@{b}/LOG ON@{ub}
     Begins logging to the log file

@{b}/LOG <filename>@{ub}
     Sets the path and name of the log file.


@EndNode

@Node "LUSERS" "AmIRC.guide/LUSERS"
@Toc "Commands"

Commands
========

LUSERS
------

Usage: @{b}/LUSERS (no arguments)@{ub}

Returns information on the current network. Specifically on the number
of users present.

EXAMPLES:

@{b}/LUSERS@{ub}
     This will return information on the users on the current network.


@EndNode

@Node "M" "AmIRC.guide/M"
@Toc "Commands"

Commands
========

M
-

Usage: @{b}/M nick_or_channel[,nick,...] text@{ub}

Sends a Private Message to one or more users. Note that this is
different from a @{"/DCC Chat" Link "DCC"}, in that /M (PRIVMSG) is sent through the
IRC server to the recipient. Note that the @{b}TAB@{ub} key will cycle back and
forth through the users who have /MSG'ed you. This will appear in the
input string gadget, and you may simply add your message after it.

Alternative: @{"MSG" Link "MSG"} @{"RMSG" Link "RMSG"}

EXAMPLES:

@{b}/M Kenneth Heya Dude! How's Florida?@{ub}
     Send the message: @{i}"Heya Dude! How's Florida?"@{ui} to user @{i}Kenneth@{ui}.

@{b}/M Kenneth,Aerosoul I am in Pittsburgh@{ub}
     Sends the message @{i}"I am in Pittsburgh"@{ui} to @{i}Kenneth@{ui} and @{i}Aerosoul@{ui}.


@EndNode

@Node "MAP" "AmIRC.guide/MAP"
@Toc "Commands"

Commands
========

MAP
---

Usage: @{b}/MAP [server]@{ub}

MAP returns a map of all servers the network consists of. The optional
parameter is used as a mask

Related: @{"LINKS" Link "LINKS"}

EXAMPLES:

@{b}/MAP@{ub}
     Shows a map of all servers

@{b}/MAP *.*.com@{ub}
     Shows a map of all servers ending with @{i}com@{ui}.


@EndNode

@Node "ME" "AmIRC.guide/ME"
@Toc "Commands"

Commands
========

ME
--

Usage: @{b}/ME Action@{ub}

ME sends a @{"CTCP Action" Link "CTCP"} to the channel.

Related: @{"DESCRIBE" Link "DESCRIBE"}

EXAMPLES:

@{b}/ME is currently happy.@{ub}
     Sends the following text to the channel:
     '@{b}<Action>@{ub}<nick> is currently happy'.
     Where <nick> is the currently selected nickname.


@EndNode

@Node "MODE" "AmIRC.guide/MODE"
@Toc "Commands"

Commands
========

MODE
----

Usage: @{b}/MODE [channel] [+-modes [modeparms]]@{ub}

MODE is used to change the modes of a channel or a user. Only Channel
Operators can change Channel Modes. Here's a list of all available
modes:


     o - Remove Channel Operator status. Note that you cannot set ChanOp status using @{b}+o@{ub}.
     p - Private channel; Not visible in the Channel List.
     s - Secret channel; Not visible until you enter.
     i - Invite-only channel; Only accessible on invitation.
     t - Topic protection; Settable by Channel Operators only.
     n - No Messages; No messages from clients outside channel.
     m - Moderated channel; Only ChanOps and people with @{"VOICE" Link "VOICE"} can send public messages.
     l - Limit: Set maximum number of users allowed on channel.
     b - Ban: Set a ban to keep users out.
     v - Voice: Give/take the ability to speak on a Moderated channel.
     k - Keyword: Set a channel keyword (password).

Related: @{"BAN" Link "BAN"} @{"BANDEL" Link "BANDEL"} @{"INVITE" Link "INVITE"} @{"OP" Link "OP"} @{"DEOP" Link "DEOP"} @{"TOPIC" Link "TOPIC"} @{"VOICE" Link "VOICE"} @{"UMODE" Link "UMODE"} @{"UNVOICE" Link "UNVOICE"}

EXAMPLES:

@{b}/MODE #AmIRC +tm@{ub}
     Sets topic protection and makes channel @{i}#AmIRC@{ui} moderated.

@{b}/MODE #AmIRC -o Sarek@{ub}
     Removes channel operator status from user @{i}'Sarek'@{ui} on channel
     @{i}#AmIRC@{ui}.

@{b}/MODE #AmIRC +l 50@{ub}
     Sets limit of 50 users on @{i}#AmIRC@{ui}.

@{b}/MODE #AmIRC -l@{ub}
     Removes the limit form @{i}#AmIRC@{ui}.


@EndNode

@Node "MOTD" "AmIRC.guide/MOTD"
@Toc "Commands"

Commands
========

MOTD
----

Usage: @{b}/MOTD (no arguments)@{ub}

This returns the @{i}Message Of The Day@{ui} of the server currently connected
to.

EXAMPLES:

@{b}/MOTD@{ub}
     Shows the current Message Of The Day of the server.


@EndNode

@Node "MSG" "AmIRC.guide/MSG"
@Toc "Commands"

Commands
========

MSG (PRIVMSG)
-------------

Usage: @{b}/MSG nick_or_channel[,nick,...] text@{ub}

Sends a Private Message to one or more users. Note that this is
different from a @{"/DCC Chat" Link "DCC"}, in that a /MSG (PRIVMSG) is sent through
the IRC server to the recipient. Note that the @{b}TAB@{ub} key will cycle back
and forth through the users who have /MSG'ed you. This will appear in
the input string gadget, and you may simply add your message after it.

Alternatives: @{"M" Link "M"} @{"RMSG" Link "RMSG"} EXAMPLES:

@{b}/MSG Kenneth Heya Dude! How's Florida?@{ub}
     Send the message: "Heya Dude! How's Florida?" to user 'Kenneth'.

@{b}/MSG Kenneth,Aerosoul I am in Pittsburgh@{ub}
     Sends the message "I am in Pittsburgh" to Kenneth and Aerosoul.


@EndNode

@Node "NAMES" "AmIRC.guide/NAMES"
@Toc "Commands"

Commands
========

Names
-----

Usage @{b}/NAMES channel[,channel[,...]]@{ub}

Gives a list of nicknames on any channel visible to the user (not
secret or private, or one actually joined by the user performing the
command).

EXAMPLES:

@{b}/NAMES #AmIRC,#amigaGER@{ub}
     Will list all users on channels #AmIRC and #amigaGER, provided the
     channels are visible to the user.

@{b}/NAMES@{ub}
     Will return a list of all visible channels and users (Strongly
     Discouraged!)


@EndNode

@Node "NICK" "AmIRC.guide/NICK"
@Toc "Commands"

Commands
========

NICK
----

Usage: @{b}/NICK NewNick@{ub}

NICK is used to give yourself a nickname or change your current one. If
the chosen nick is already in use, you will be notified of this and
prompted for a new nick.

Alternative: @{"IRCNAME" Link "IRCNAME"}

EXAMPLES:

@{b}/NICK Phalanx@{ub}
     Sets your nickname to 'Phalanx'


@EndNode

@Node "NOTE" "AmIRC.guide/NOTE"
@Toc "Commands"

Commands
========

NOTE
----

Usage: @{b}/NOTE [undefined]@{ub}

This command is still a leftover from the past and is not supported any
more by any current servers.


@EndNode

@Node "NOTICE" "AmIRC.guide/NOTICE"
@Toc "Commands"

Commands
========

NOTICE
------

Usage: @{b}/NOTICE nick_or_channel[,nick,...] text@{ub}

/NOTICE is usually used by Bots or clients being controlled by scripts.
/NOTICE messages must never be responded to by an automatic reply.

See @{"MSG" Link "MSG"} for syntax examples.


@EndNode

@Node "NOTIFY" "AmIRC.guide/NOTIFY"
@Toc "Commands"

Commands
========

NOTIFY
------

Usage: @{b}/NOTIFY [nick]@{ub}

With NOTIFY you can specify the nick of a user you want to be notified
of when he joins IRC. You can set the notification event in the
@{"Events Window" Link "Events"} of the Settings. When no nick is submitted you will be
presented with the @{"NOTIFY Window" Link "Windows"}.

EXAMPLES:

@{b}/NOTIFY Bert@{ub}
     You will be notified when user @{i}Bert@{ui} is joining the IRC network.


@EndNode

@Node "OP" "AmIRC.guide/OP"
@Toc "Commands"

Commands
========

OP
--

Usage: @{b}/OP [channel] nick[,nick...]@{ub}

With this command you can set the Channel Operator status of a user or
several users at once.

EXAMPLES:

@{b}/OP Bert,Franky@{ub}
     Sets the @{i}Channel Operator@{ui} status for users @{i}Bert@{ui} and @{i}Franky@{ui}


@EndNode

@Node "OPER" "AmIRC.guide/OPER"
@Toc "Commands"

Commands
========

OPER
----

Usage: @{b}/OPER user password@{ub}

Allows users to set their IRC Operator status. You will need to know the
password to become IRC Operator. Using /OPER without it's parameters
will present you with a requester where you can enter your username and
password.

EXAMPLES:

@{b}/OPER Bill Bucks@{ub}
     Sets user @{i}Bill@{ui} IRC Operator status using password @{i}Bucks@{ui}.


@EndNode

@Node "PART" "AmIRC.guide/PART"
@Toc "Commands"

Commands
========

PART
----

Usage: @{b}/PART [Channel[,Channel...]]@{ub}

Leaves a channel. If you don't give a channel name as a parameter, the
channel currently bound to the window in which in the command is
entered will be left.

Alternative: @{"LEAVE" Link "LEAVE"}

Related: @{"CHANNEL" Link "CHANNEL"} @{"CYCLE" Link "CYCLE"} @{"JOIN" Link "JOIN"}

EXAMPLES:

@{b}/PART@{ub}
     Leave the channel currently bound to this window.

@{b}/PART #AmigaGER@{ub}
     Leave channel @{i}#AmigaGER@{ui}.


@EndNode

@Node "PING" "AmIRC.guide/PING"
@Toc "Commands"

Commands
========

PING
----

Usage: @{b}/PING [nick]@{ub}

Sends a @{"/CTCP Ping" Link "CTCP"} to the user with the submitted nick and return the
time it took to receive it back. If no nick is given the PING will be
sent to the server.

Related: @{"CTCP" Link "CTCP"}

EXAMPLES:

@{b}/PING Bill@{ub}
     Will send a PING to @{i}Bill@{ui} and return:
          @{b}«Pong»@{ub}  PING Response received from Bill: 2.4s


@EndNode

@Node "QKICK" "AmIRC.guide/QKICK"
@Toc "Commands"

Commands
========

QKICK
-----

Usage: @{b}/QKICK [channel] nick[,nick...] [reason]@{ub}

This command is use to kick or ban a person and presents you with a
window in which you can select the hostmask use for the ban. Pressing
either the @{i}Kick@{ui} or @{i}Kick&Ban@{ui} button will kick(ban) the user. Here's the
hostmasks offered:

     nick!*user@host.do.main : Bans a specific user with a specific nick.
     *!*@*.do.main : Ban all users of @{i}do.main@{ui}.
     *!*user@host.do.main : Ban a user with a specific host.
     *!*@ip1.ip2.ip3.* : Numerical hostmask, banning all users in a domain.

Alternative: @{"QKICKBAN" Link "QKICKBAN"}

Related: @{"BAN" Link "BAN"} @{"BANDEL" Link "BANDEL"} @{"BANLIST" Link "BANLIST"} @{"KICK" Link "KICK"} @{"KICKBAN" Link "KICKBAN"}

EXAMPLES:

@{b}/QKICK@{ub}
     You will be presented with a Kick/Ban window


@EndNode

@Node "QKICKBAN" "AmIRC.guide/QKICKBAN"
@Toc "Commands"

Commands
========

QKICKBAN
--------

Usage: @{b}/QKICKBAN [channel] nick[,nick...] [reason]@{ub}

This command is use to kick or ban a person and presents you with a
window in which you can select the hostmask use for the ban. Pressing
either the @{i}Kick@{ui} or @{i}Kick&Ban@{ui} button will kick(ban) the user. Here's the
hostmasks offered:

     nick!*user@host.do.main : Bans a specific user with a specific nick.
     *!*@*.do.main : Ban all users of @{i}do.main@{ui}.
     *!*user@host.do.main : Ban a user with a specific host.
     *!*@ip1.ip2.ip3.* : Numerical hostmask, banning all users in a domain.

Alternative: @{"QKICK" Link "QKICK"}

Related: @{"BAN" Link "BAN"} @{"BANDEL" Link "BANDEL"} @{"BANLIST" Link "BANLIST"} @{"KICK" Link "KICK"} @{"KICKBAN" Link "KICKBAN"}

EXAMPLES:

@{b}/QKICKBAN@{ub}
     You will be presented with a Kick/Ban window


@EndNode

@Node "QUERY" "AmIRC.guide/QUERY"
@Toc "Commands"

Commands
========

QUERY
-----

Usage: @{b}/QUERY nick [+|-|msg]@{ub}

With this command you can open a Query window for a specific user. All
@{"PrivMessages" Link "MSG"} from this user will be diverted to this window.  You can
also @{"PING" Link "PING"} or @{"WHOIS" Link "WHOIS"} the other user, or you may initiate a @{i}'DCC Send'@{ui} or
@{i}'DCC Chat'@{ui}. Starting a @{i}'DCC Chat'@{ui} from this window will allow you to
carry on a dialogue with the remote user through the window. If you
issue the command with a nick that has an iconified Query window, it
will be uniconified. When using the (optional) @{i}+@{ui} argument the Query
window will be opened as a page in the current window, with the @{i}-@{ui} a
seperate Query window will be opened, regardless of the 'Use pages by
default?' setting.  With the optional [msg] argument you can
immediately send a message to the user when opening the Query window.
Please note that you can only use one of the arguments at a time.

EXAMPLES:

@{b}/QUERY Hero@{ub}
     Will open a Query window with user @{i}Hero@{ui}.

@{b}/QUERY Hero -@{ub}
     Will open a new Query window, regardless of the default setting.

@{b}/QUERY Hero Good Evening@{ub}
     Will open a Query window and send the message @{i}Good Evening@{ui}
     immediately


@EndNode

@Node "QUIT" "AmIRC.guide/QUIT"
@Toc "Commands"

Commands
========

QUIT
----

Usage: @{b}/QUIT [Quit message]@{ub}

Used to end an IRC session. The optional [Quit message] is the text that
will be displayed upon quitting.

Related: @{"SERVER" Link "SERVER"}

EXAMPLES:

@{b}/QUIT Gone to have lunch@{ub}
     Will quit AmIRC and send the text @{i}'Gone to have lunch'@{ui} to all
     joined channels.


@EndNode

@Node "QUOTE" "AmIRC.guide/QUOTE"
@Toc "Commands"

Commands
========

QUOTE
-----

Usage: @{b}/QUOTE Raw_data_to_send_to_IRC_server@{ub}

Sends text directly to the IRC server without any further processing.
@{i}Warning:@{ui} Don't even think about using this command without interior
knowledge of the IRC protocol, or you might run into severe trouble.
See `RFC 1459' for a description of the IRC protocol.

Alternative: @{"RAW" Link "RAW"}

EXAMPLES:

@{b}/QUOTE JOIN #IRC-Heros@{ub}
     Send the string @{i}JOIN #IRC-Heros@{ui} directly to the IRC server.


@EndNode

@Node "RAW" "AmIRC.guide/RAW"
@Toc "Commands"

Commands
========

RAW
---

Usage: @{b}/RAW Raw_data_to_send_to_IRC_server@{ub}

Sends text directly to the IRC server without any further processing.
@{i}Warning:@{ui} Don't even think about using this command without interior
knowledge of the IRC protocol, or you might run into severe trouble.
See `RFC 1459' for a description of the IRC protocol.

Alternative: @{"QUOTE" Link "QUOTE"}

EXAMPLES:

@{b}/RAW JOIN #IRC-Heros@{ub}
     Send the string @{i}JOIN #IRC-Heros@{ui} directly to the IRC server.


@EndNode

@Node "RECONNECT" "AmIRC.guide/RECONNECT"
@Toc "Commands"

Commands
========

RECONNECT
---------

Usage: @{b}/RECONNECT@{ub}

This command will reconnect you to the current server. It is the same
as the menu item and can be useful when a connection is either timed out
or lagging.

EXAMPLES:

@{b}/RECONNECT@{ub}
     Will reconnect you to the current server.


@EndNode

@Node "REHASH" "AmIRC.guide/REHASH"
@Toc "Commands"

Commands
========

REHASH
------

Usage: @{b}/REHASH (no arguments)@{ub}

The rehash message can be used by the operator to force the server to
re-read and process its configuration file. It's can only be used by
IRC Operators.

EXAMPLES:

@{b}/REHASH@{ub}
     Will cause the IRC server to reread it's configuration file.


@EndNode

@Node "RELOAD" "AmIRC.guide/RELOAD"
@Toc "Commands"

Commands
========

RELOAD
------

Usage: @{b}/RELOAD plugin [FORCE]@{ub}

This command will make AmIRC reload a plugin that has already been
loaded. This can be useful if the plugin has been updated. The FORCE
option will force AmIRC to reload if the plugin refuses to unload.

Related: @{"LOAD" Link "LOAD"} @{"UNLOAD" Link "UNLOAD"}

EXAMPLES:

@{b}/RELOAD XDCC@{ub}
     Will make AmIRC reload the XDCC plugin.


@EndNode

@Node "RESTART" "AmIRC.guide/RESTART"
@Toc "Commands"

Commands
========

RESTART
-------

Usage: @{b}/RESTART (no arguments)@{ub}

This command is used to reset the IRC server. Note that this command
can only be used by IRC Operators.

EXAMPLES:

@{b}/RESTART@{ub}
     Will reset the IRC server


@EndNode

@Node "RMSG" "AmIRC.guide/RMSG"
@Toc "Commands"

Commands
========

RMSG
----

Usage: @{b}/RMSG nick_or_channel[,nick,...] text@{ub}

Sends a Private Message to one or more users. Note that this is
different from a @{"/DCC Chat" Link "DCC"}, in that /M (PRIVMSG) is sent through the
IRC server to the recipient. Note that the @{b}TAB@{ub} key will cycle back and
forth through the users who have /MSG'ed you. This will appear in the
input string gadget, and you may simply add your message after it.

Alternative: @{"M" Link "M"} @{"MSG" Link "MSG"}

EXAMPLES:

@{b}/RMSG Kenneth Heya Dude! How's Florida?@{ub}
     Send the message: "Heya Dude! How's Florida?" to user 'Kenneth'.

@{b}/RMSG Kenneth,Aerosoul I am in Pittsburgh@{ub}
     Sends the message "I am in Pittsburgh" to Kenneth and Aerosoul.


@EndNode

@Node "RX" "AmIRC.guide/RX"
@Toc "Commands"

Commands
========

RX
--

Usage: @{b}/RX rxcommand [parms]@{ub}

This command is used to start any of the Arexx commands that are in
AmIRC's Rexx directory. A complete @{"Arexx" Link "Rexx"} guide is also available.

Related: @{"RXRETURN" Link "RXRETURN"}

EXAMPLES:

@{b}/RX leave@{ub}
     Will start the Arexx command @{i}'Leave.amirx'@{ui} if present.


@EndNode

@Node "RXRETURN" "AmIRC.guide/RXRETURN"
@Toc "Commands"

Commands
========

RXRETURN
--------

Usage: @{b}/RXRETURN Command [Rest]@{ub}

/RXRETURN is only useful to ARexx script authors. It will cause any
pending GETREXXLINE commands to immediately return with the arguments
given to it."

Related: @{"RX" Link "RX"}


@EndNode

@Node "SERVER" "AmIRC.guide/SERVER"
@Toc "Commands"

Commands
========

SERVER
------

Usage: @{b}/SERVER [server [port [password]]]@{ub}

You can use this command to connect to a different server or to get
information about the currently connected server.

Related: @{"QUIT" Link "QUIT"}

EXAMPLES:

@{b}/SERVER irc.server.com@{ub}
     Connects you to the server @{i}irc.server.com@{ui}

@{b}/SERVER@{ub}
     Shows current connection information


@EndNode

@Node "SILENCE" "AmIRC.guide/SILENCE"
@Toc "Commands"

Commands
========

SILENCE
-------

Usage: @{b}/SILENCE [[+|-]nick|userhost]@{ub}

SILENCE can be used to block all CTCP traffic from a certain user or
userhost.  Meaning for instance that no @{"MSG" Link "MSG"} or @{"DCC CHAT" Link "DCC"} will be received
from that user.

Related: @{"IGNORE" Link "IGNORE"} @{"UNIGNORE" Link "UNIGNORE"}

EXAMPLES:

@{b}/SILENCE@{ub}
     Shows a list of all currently @{i}silenced@{ui} users.

@{b}/SILENCE +Bill@{ub}
     Will @{i}silence@{ui} user @{i}Bill@{ui}

@{b}/SILENCE -Friend@{ub}
     Will remove @{i}Friend@{ui} from the @{i}Silence@{ui} list.


@EndNode

@Node "SOUND" "AmIRC.guide/SOUND"
@Toc "Commands"

Commands
========

SOUND
-----

Usage: @{b}/SOUND soundfile[.wav] action_text@{ub}

This command can be used to have all clients on a channel play a
certain sound.  Please note that the sound file must be present on the
user's system to be able to play it, so don't use this randomly as
nobody will hear a thing when the submitted filename is not found.

EXAMPLES:

@{b}/SOUND Burp@{ub}
     Will play the sound file @{i}Burp.wav@{ui} on all user's system, if found!

@{b}/SOUND Burp Excuse me!@{ub}
     Will play the soundfile and send the text @{i}'Excuse me!'@{ui} with it.


@EndNode

@Node "SQUIT" "AmIRC.guide/SQUIT"
@Toc "Commands"

Commands
========

SQUIT
-----

Usage: @{b}/SQUIT server@{ub}

This command is used to disconnect a server from the network. Note that
only IRC Operators have access to this command.

EXAMPLES:

@{b}/SQUIT irc.server.com@{ub}
     Will quit server @{i}irc.server.com@{ui}


@EndNode

@Node "STATS" "AmIRC.guide/STATS"
@Toc "Commands"

Commands
========

STATS
-----

Usage: @{b}/STATS [server] [query]@{ub}

The STATS command is used to query statistics of certain server. If the
[server] parameter is omitted, only the end of statistics reply is sent
back. The implementation of this command is highly dependent on the
server which replies, although the server must be able to supply
information as described by the queries below (or similar).

The currently supported queries are:

     c - Returns a list of servers which the server may connect to or allow connections
     from.
     h - Returns a list of servers which are either forced to be treated as leaves or
     allowed to act as hubs.
     i - Returns a list of hosts which the server allows a client to connect from.
     k - Returns a list of banned username/hostname combinations for that server.
     l - Returns a list of the server's connections, showing how long each connection
     has been established and the traffic over that connection in bytes and messages
     for each direction.
     m - Returns a list of commands supported by the server and the usage count for
     each if the usage count is non zero.
     o - Returns a list of hosts from which normal clients may become operators.
     y - Show Y (Class) lines from server's configuration file.
     u - Returns a string showing how long the server has been up.

EXAMPLES:

@{b}/STATS irc.server.com u@{ub}
     Shows how long server @{i}irc.server.com@{ui} has been up


@EndNode

@Node "SUMMON" "AmIRC.guide/SUMMON"
@Toc "Commands"

Commands
========

SUMMON
------

Usage: @{b}/SUMMON user@{ub}

The SUMMON command can be used to give users who are on a host running
an IRC server a message asking them to please join IRC. This message is
only sent if the target server (a) has SUMMON enabled, (b) the user is
logged in and (c) the server process can write to the user's tty (or
similar).

EXAMPLES:

@{b}/SUMMON John@{ub}
     Will ask user @{i}John@{ui} to join IRC.


@EndNode

@Node "TIME" "AmIRC.guide/TIME"
@Toc "Commands"

Commands
========

TIME
----

Usage: @{b}/TIME [server]@{ub}

Returns the local time from the server. If the optional [server]
argument is given, then that servers local time will be returned.

EXAMPLES:

@{b}/TIME irc.pitt.edu@{ub}
     Returns the local time from server @{i}irc.pitt.edu@{ui}.


@EndNode

@Node "TOPIC" "AmIRC.guide/TOPIC"
@Toc "Commands"

Commands
========

TOPIC
-----

Usage: @{b}/TOPIC [channel] [New Topic]@{ub}

The topic command alone will display the channels topic. If the optional
[New Topic] argument is given, the topic will be changed to the
argument given, provided that the topic is not protected, or the user
issuing the command is an operator on the channel.

Related: @{"MODE" Link "MODE"}

EXAMPLES:

@{b}/TOPIC #AmIRC@{ub}
     Will display the current topic on #AmIRC.

@{b}/TOPIC #AmIRC Amigas Rule!@{ub}
     Will replace the current topic of #AmIRC with the topic 'Amigas
     Rule'


@EndNode

@Node "TRACE" "AmIRC.guide/TRACE"
@Toc "Commands"

Commands
========

TRACE
-----

Usage: @{b}/TRACE [server|nick]@{ub}

TRACE is used to find the route to specific server. If the parameter is
omitted, it will return which servers the current server has a direct
connection to. If the destination given is a nickname, only a reply for
that nickname is given. If the destination is an actual server, then
the destination server is required to report all servers and users which
are connected to it, although only operators are permitted to see users
present.

EXAMPLES:

@{b}/TRACE Bill@{ub}
     Traces connection to user @{i}Bill@{ui}.


@EndNode

@Node "UMODE" "AmIRC.guide/UMODE"
@Toc "Commands"

Commands
========

UMODE
-----

Usage: @{b}/UMODE [usermodes]@{ub}

UMODE is used to set your own usermodes. The available options are:

     o - Chan Op: Sets/Takes Channel Operator status
     i - Invisible: Sets Visible/Invisible (in global userlist).
     w - Wallops: Allows receiving of texts sent to all Operators.
     s - Server Notices: Allows receiving of Server Notices.
Related: @{"MODE" Link "MODE"}

EXAMPLES:

@{b}/UMODE i@{ub}
     Makes you invisible to the global userlist.


@EndNode

@Node "UNHIGHLITE" "AmIRC.guide/UNHIGHLITE"
@Toc "Commands"

Commands
========

UNHIGHLITE
----------

Usage: @{b}/UNHIGHLITE [item]@{ub}

HIGHLITE can be used to light up certain texts. They will be shown in a
colour that's defined in the @{"Settings" Link "Colors"}.

You can also change Highlighting using the @{"Hilight Window" Link "Lists"}.

Alternative: @{"UNHILITE" Link "UNHILITE"}

Related: @{"HIGHLITE" Link "HIGHLITE"} @{"HILITE" Link "HILITE"}

EXAMPLES:

@{b}/UNHIGHLITE MyName@{ub}
     Will remove @{i}MyName@{ui} from the @{i}Highlight List@{ui}.


@EndNode

@Node "UNHILITE" "AmIRC.guide/UNHILITE"
@Toc "Commands"

Commands
========

UNHILITE
--------

HIGHLITE can be used to light up certain texts. They will be shown in a
colour that's defined in the @{"Settings" Link "Colors"}.

You can also change Highlighting using the @{"Hilight Window" Link "Lists"}.

Alternative: @{"UNHILITE" Link "UNHILITE"}

Related: @{"HIGHLITE" Link "HIGHLITE"} @{"HILITE" Link "HILITE"}

Usage: @{b}/UNHILITE [item]@{ub}

EXAMPLES:

@{b}/UNHILITE MyName@{ub}
     Will remove @{i}MyName@{ui} from the @{i}Highlight List@{ui}.


@EndNode

@Node "UNIGNORE" "AmIRC.guide/UNIGNORE"
@Toc "Commands"

Commands
========

UNIGNORE
--------

Usage: @{b}/UNIGNORE [userhost|nick]@{ub}

Removes the Ignore state of a user. Will show current ignores when no
argument is submitted.

Related: @{"IGNORE" Link "IGNORE"} @{"SILENCE" Link "SILENCE"}

EXAMPLES:

@{b}/UNIGNORE@{ub}
     Shows a list of all currently ignored users

@{b}/UNIGNORE Franky@{ub}
     Will remove all ignores on @{i}Franky@{ui}


@EndNode

@Node "UNLOAD" "AmIRC.guide/UNLOAD"
@Toc "Commands"

Commands
========

UNLOAD
------

Usage: @{b}/UNLOAD plugin [FORCE]@{ub}

Will make AmIRC unload a plugin. The FORCE option will force the plugin
to be unloaded.

Related: @{"LOAD" Link "LOAD"} @{"RELOAD" Link "RELOAD"}

EXAMPLES:

@{b}/UNLOAD XDCC@{ub}
     Makes AmIRC unload the XDCC plugin.


@EndNode

@Node "UNVOICE" "AmIRC.guide/UNVOICE"
@Toc "Commands"

Commands
========

UNVOICE
-------

Usage: @{b}/UNVOICE [channel] nick[,nick...]@{ub}

Will remove a user's Voice status. You can specify a certain channel
and submit multiple users.

Related: @{"VOICE" Link "VOICE"}

EXAMPLES:

@{b}/UNVOICE Boy@{ub}
     Will remove the Voice status of @{i}Boy@{ui}


@EndNode

@Node "UPING" "AmIRC.guide/UPING"
@Toc "Commands"

Commands
========

UNPING
------

Usage: @{b}/UPING host@{ub}

UPING is used by IRCops to ping a certain host. Mainly used for
debugging the network and see if connections are alive.

EXAMPLES:

@{b}/UPING irc.network.com@{ub}
     Send a Ping packet to @{i}irc.network.com@{ui}.


@EndNode

@Node "USERS" "AmIRC.guide/USERS"
@Toc "Commands"

Commands
========

USERS
-----

Usage: @{b}/USERS [host]@{ub}

The USERS command returns a list of users logged into the server in a
similar format to who, rusers and finger. This command is frequently
disabled for security related reasons.

Related: @{"FINDHOST" Link "FINDHOST"} @{"USERHOST" Link "USERHOST"} @{"WHO" Link "WHO"}

EXAMPLES:

@{b}/USERS *.microsoft.com@{ub}
     Will show all user connected to @{i}*.microsoft.com@{ui}.


@EndNode

@Node "USERHOST" "AmIRC.guide/USERHOST"
@Toc "Commands"

Commands
========

USERHOST
--------

Usage: @{b}/USERHOST nick[,nick[,...]]@{ub}

Returns the @{i}login@domain@{ui} for the specified nickname(s). Up to five
nicknames may be specified, each separated by a <space>.

Related: @{"FINDHOST" Link "FINDHOST"} @{"USERS" Link "USERS"} @{"WHO" Link "WHO"}

EXAMPLES:

@{b}/USERHOST DuRaN@{ub}
     Returns: @{i}DuRaN@{ui} is @{i}DuRaN@calci.amiganet.pgh.net@{ui}


@EndNode

@Node "VERSION" "AmIRC.guide/VERSION"
@Toc "Commands"

Commands
========

VERSION
-------

Usage @{b}/VERSION [nick|server]@{ub}

Returns the version of the server's software. If the optional [server]
argument is given, returns the version of the specified server's
software. When a user's nick is given instead it will return the user's
client software version and info.

EXAMPLES:

@{b}/VERSION *.edu@{ub}
     Returns server version information for all servers matching
     @{i}'*.edu'@{ui}.

@{b}/VERSION Franky@{ub}
     Will return information and version of @{i}Franky's@{ui} client software.


@EndNode

@Node "VOICE" "AmIRC.guide/VOICE"
@Toc "Commands"

Commands
========

VOICE
-----

Usage @{b}/VOICE [channel] nick[,nick...]@{ub}

You can give a user a @{i}Voice@{ui} with this command. A voice is needed on a
@{i}Moderated@{ui} channel to be able to speak. (See @{"Channel Modes" Link "MODE"} for details).

Related: @{"UNVOICE" Link "UNVOICE"}

EXAMPLES:

@{b}/VOICE Sinatra@{ub}
     Gives a @{i}Voice@{ui} to user @{i}Sinatra@{ui}.


@EndNode

@Node "WALLOPS" "AmIRC.guide/WALLOPS"
@Toc "Commands"

Commands
========

WALLOPS
-------

Usage @{b}/WALLOPS text_to_broadcast@{ub}

Sends a text to all Operators who have 'Receiving WALLOPS' enabled.
This command is mainly used by servers.

EXAMPLES:

@{b}/WALLOPS Greeting to you all!@{ub}
     Sends the text @{i}'Greeting to you all!'@{ui} to all Operators.


@EndNode

@Node "WHO" "AmIRC.guide/WHO"
@Toc "Commands"

Commands
========

WHO
---

Usage: @{b}/WHO channel|pattern@{ub}

Returns a generated list of all users matching the criteria passed to
the command, i/e. everyone at a particular channel, or matching a
particular pattern.

Related: @{"FINDHOST" Link "FINDHOST"} @{"USERS" Link "USERS"} @{"USERHOST" Link "USERHOST"}

EXAMPLES:

@{b}/WHO *.cmu.edu@{ub}
     Will list all users at the @{i}cmu.edu@{ui} domain.

@{b}/WHO #Amiga@{ub}
     Shows all users on @{i}#Amiga@{ui}.


@EndNode

@Node "WHOIS" "AmIRC.guide/WHOIS"
@Toc "Commands"

Commands
========

WHOIS
-----

Usage: @{b}/WHOIS nick[,nick[,...]]@{ub}

Returns information about the specified user or users, that you are
allowed to see.

EXAMPLES:

@{b}/WHOIS Phalanx@{ub}
     Returns available information about user @{i}'Phalanx'@{ui}.


@EndNode

@Node "WHOWAS" "AmIRC.guide/WHOWAS"
@Toc "Commands"

Commands
========

WHOWAS
------

Usage @{b}/WHOWAS nick[,nick[,...]]@{ub}

Returns information on a nick that no longer exists, due to the user
leaving the server or changing their nick.

EXAMPLES:

@{b}/WHOWAS Aerosoul@{ub}
     Checks for and returns available information on the nick
     @{i}'Aerosoul'@{ui}.


@EndNode

@Node "Configuration" "AmIRC.guide/Configuration"
@Next "ARexx"
@Prev "Commands"
@Toc "Main"

Customizing your environment
****************************

Overview
========

Now that you have AmIRC running, you may want to get it to operate the
way you want it to, and to look pleasing as well. This is achieved
through both the MUI preferences and AmIRC's Menu options.


 @{" MUI Preferences " Link "MUI Preferences"}       Changing MUI Settings
 @{" AmIRC Setup " Link "AmIRC Setup"}           Changing AmIRC Setup


@EndNode

@Node "MUI Preferences" "AmIRC.guide/MUI Preferences"
@Toc "Configuration"

MUI Settings
************

Changing MUI Settings
=====================

Most of the configuration dealing with how AmIRC's GUI appears can be
customized with MUI. Check the @{i}MUI Settings...@{ui} entry under the @{i}Settings@{ui}
menu. This will pop up MUI's interface, allowing you to setup AmIRC's
MUI Prefs, without disturbing any of your other MUI configurations. Read
the documentation for MUI to learn more about the operation of MUI
Preferences.


@EndNode

@Node "AmIRC Setup" "AmIRC.guide/AmIRC Setup"
@Toc "Configuration"

AmIRC Configuration
*******************

Customizing your environment
============================

Most of the setup functions appear in the @{i}Setup@{ui} entry under the
@{i}Settings@{ui} menu. Here you will get a window that will allow you to
access several pages that deal with configuring AmIRC.



 @{" Messages " Link "Messages"}             Messages Page
 @{" Events " Link "Events"}               Events Page
 @{" Actions " Link "Actions"}              Actions Page
 @{" Lists " Link "Lists"}                Lists Page
 @{" Interface " Link "Interface"}            Interface Page
 @{" Colors " Link "Colors"}               Colors Page
 @{" Windows " Link "Window"}              Windows Page
 @{" Logging " Link "Logging"}              Logging Page
 @{" FKeys " Link "FKeys"}                Function Keys Page
 @{" Misc " Link "Misc"}                 Miscellaneous Page


@EndNode

@Node "Messages" "AmIRC.guide/Messages"
@Toc "AmIRC Setup"

AmIRC Configuration
*******************

Messages Page
=============

Misc Messages
-------------

@{b}CTCP Userinfo@{ub}
     The text in this string is what will be returned to a user who
     sends @{"/CTCP userinfo" Link "CTCP"} to your client.

@{b}KICK Reason@{ub}
     If you are a channel operator and @{"KICK" Link "KICK"} another user from the
     Channel, this text will appear as the reason for the /KICK.

Quit Messages
-------------

@{b}Exit@{ub}
     This will appear to users in the channel when you exit AmIRC.

@{b}New Server@{ub}
     This text will appear to users in the channel when you select
     @{i}Select Server@{ui} in the @{i}AmIRC@{ui} menu, and pick a new server to connect
     to.

@{b}System reset@{ub}
     This is the text to appear if you reboot your amiga (Ctrl-
     Amiga-Amiga) while connected to a server.

AWAY Messages
-------------

@{b}Default@{ub}
     This is the text that will appear when you are set @{i}AWAY@{ui} by
     selecting the @{i}Marked Away?@{ui} item in the @{i}User Modes@{ui} menu or using
     the @{"AWAY" Link "AWAY"} command

@{b}AutoAWAY@{ub}
     Text that appears when you are automatically set away due to
     inactivity.

@{b}Timeout@{ub}
     This sets how much time will pass before AmIRC assumes you are
     away from the computer and marks you as @{i}AWAY@{ui}. If set to 0 (Zero),
     time-out will be disabled.

@{b}UnAWAY@{ub}
     This cycle gadget allows you to choose the conditions of which
     AmIRC will automatically set you to @{i}Not AWAY@{ui}.


@EndNode

@Node "Events" "AmIRC.guide/Events"
@Toc "AmIRC Setup"

AmIRC Configuration
*******************

Events Page
===========

Here you may define certain actions to take place upon incoming events.
These actions can be as simple as a warning beep from your Amiga, or a
complex and powerful @{"Rexx" Link "Rexx"} command. The following text first explains
the functions of the columns of this page, and then goes on to explain
what each event is.

Columns
-------

@{b}Event@{ub}
     The particular event for the action to take place on.

@{b}Deiconify@{ub}
     If AmIRC is iconified, this will uniconify and bring to front the
     AmIRC window on the occurrence of the event.

@{b}Beep@{ub}
     This will perform a system beep on the occurrence of the event

@{b}Sound@{ub}
     If a sound sample is preferred for the event, you may use the
     requester gadget to pick a sound to play instead of the system
     beep. Please Note, AmIRC uses the DataTypes of OS 3.x for sounds,
     and you will not be able to use this feature under OS 2.x.

@{b}Vol@{ub}
     This sets the volume for the sound sample. The valid range for the
     volume is 0 - 64.  This is a slider gadget. The small gadget just
     to the left of this slider gadget can be used to test the selected
     sound file.

@{b}Rexx Command@{ub}
     Here you may configure a @{"Rexx" Link "Rexx"} script to be run on the occurrence
     of the event.

Events
------

@{b}Any Message@{ub}
     This event occurs on any incoming public message.

@{b}Private Msg@{ub}
     This event occurs when you receive an incoming private @{"MSG" Link "MSG"} or
     @{"DCC Chat" Link "DCC"} message.

@{b}Notice@{ub}
     This event occurs when an operator sends out a @{"NOTICE" Link "NOTICE"}.

@{b}CTCP request@{ub}
     This event occurs when your client receives any @{"CTCP" Link "CTCP"} request. (For
     example /CTCP Time, or /CTCP Version)

@{b}DCC request@{ub}
     This event occurs on receiving a @{"DCC" Link "DCC"} file transfer request or chat
     request.

@{b}Join@{ub}
     This event occurs when anyone @{"joins" Link "JOIN"} the channel you are currently
     on.

@{b}Kick@{ub}
     This event occurs when anyone is @{"kicked" Link "KICK"} from the channel you are
     currently on.

@{b}Mode change@{ub}
     This event occurs when the channel mode is changed for the channel
     you are currently on. E.g. If someone is @{"/OP" Link "OP"}ed or /DeOPed, or if
     the channel is made private, etc.

@{b}ISON Notify@{ub}
     This event occurs when AmIRC 'sees' a user that is configured in
     your @{i}Notify list@{ui}.

@{b}Connection@{ub}
     This event occurs when AmIRC makes a connection to an IRC server.

@{b}Invite@{ub}
     This event occurs when another user @{"invites" Link "INVITE"} you to join a channel
     that is currently set to @{"MODE" Link "MODE"} @{i}Invite Only@{ui}.

@{b}Highlite@{ub}
     This even occurs upon receiving text that is configured in the
     @{i}Hilite@{ui} section of the @{"Lists" Link "Lists"} setup.


@EndNode

@Node "Actions" "AmIRC.guide/Actions"
@Toc "AmIRC Setup"

AmIRC Configuration
*******************

Actions Page
============

Action buttons
--------------

The main part of this window consists of a listview containing the @{b}Label@{ub}
and @{b}Operation@{ub} for all currently set up action buttons that appear
beneath the userlist in AmIRC's main window. You can specify up to 96
action buttons.  They can contain any IRC action, much like a macro. As
AmIRC doesn't allow configurable function keys to act as macros, these
buttons are preset for @{"CTCP" Link "CTCP"}, @{"DCC" Link "DCC"} and @{"MODE" Link "MODE"} operations.  Selecting an
action from the listview will place it in the gadgets below for editing.

@{b}Label:@{ub}
     This is the label that will appear on the action button.

@{b}Operation:@{ub}
     This is the operation that is executed when the action button is
     pressed. This can be anything you can enter in the channels input
     gadget. The bottom of the page contains a list with valid
     placeholders that will be replaced when the operation is executed.

@{b}Number of button pages@{ub}
     This slider determines how many button pages there will be.
     Allowing you to separate the action buttons into different pages
     so they won't take up too much space on the screen. Each page has
     a tab that allows it to be selected.  The actions can be sorted in
     the list by dragging and dropping allowing you to determine the
     content of each button page.

@{b}Add New Action@{ub}
     With this button a new action will be added to the list.

@{b}Delete Action@{ub}
     With this button the currently selected action will be removed
     from the list.

     These actions can also be accessed by clicking the right mouse
     button after selecting a users nick from the userlist.

Special
-------

On this page you can set some special actions:

@{b}Userlist doubleclick@{ub}
     This action will be performed when you double-click on a nick in
     the channel's userlist.

@{b}Nick button@{ub}
     This action will be performed when you click on the button
     containing your own nick.

The bottom bar shows all valid placeholders for these actions which
will be replaced when the operation is executed.


@EndNode

@Node "Lists" "AmIRC.guide/Lists"
@Toc "AmIRC Setup"

AmIRC Configuration
*******************

Lists Page
==========

Alias Page
----------

Here you can create aliases, or short-cuts for complex IRC commands.
The main part of the page is taken up by the listview containing all
currently set up aliases. You can modify them by selecting them.

@{b}Add New Alias@{ub}
     With this button you can add new aliases.

@{b}Delete Alias@{ub}
     With this button you can remove the currently selected alias from
     the list.

The bottom bar contains an example template. @{i}%p@{ui} will be replaced by any
arguments that you use when issuing the alias.

Ignore Page
-----------

Here you can set which users, if any, you want to @{"ignore" Link "IGNORE"}, and what kind
of messages from them to ignore.  The main part of the page consists of
the listview displaying all current ignores.  You can modify them by
selecting them.

@{b}Ignore Text@{ub}
     When this item is checked any public message send by the user will
     be ignored.

@{b}Ignore PrivMsgs@{ub}
     When this item is checked you won't see any @{"MSG" Link "MSG"} from the user.

@{b}Ignore CTCPs@{ub}
     When this item is checked you won't receive any @{"CTCP" Link "CTCP"} request from
     the user.

@{b}Add Ignore@{ub}
     With this button a new ignore will be added to the list.

@{b}Delete Ignore@{ub}
     This button will remove a selected ignore from the list.

Hilite Page
-----------

Here you may set certain text to be highlighted in order to get your
attention if that text appears.  The main part of the page is taken up
by the listview showing all currently set up patterns. You may edit any
entry by selecting it.

@{b}Add New Hilite pattern@{ub}
     With this button you can add a new pattern to the list.  You may
     set text to match the Nick, Userhost, or any keyword enclosed in
     double quotes. The Hilite patterns will ignore a pattern it
     recognizes if it was input by you, but will be activate on the
     pattern from other users.

Pattern Definitions:
--------------------

    @{b}Nick@{ub}
          This will watch the AmIRC listview for the nick that you
          specify, and highlight the text for that users message.  The
          'Nick' entry does not require double quotes.

    @{b}Userhost@{ub}
          This will watch for messages that originate from a particular
          Userhost, and highlight the text for that message. Userhost
          entries may contain wildcards.  Examples:

         @{b}fred!fdoe@doe1.powernet.edu@{ub}
               This will highlight only messages from fred at that
               particular address.

         @{b}fred!*@*@{ub}
               This will highlight messages from anyone named fred,
               regardless of address or login name.

         @{b}Fred!*@*.powernet.edu@{ub}
               This will highlight messages from anyone named fred on
               any machine on powernet.edu

         @{b}*!*@doe1.powernet.edu@{ub}
               This will highlight any messages from anyone on the doe1
               machine at powernet.edu

         @{b}*!*@*@{ub}
               This will highlight any messages from any user.

    @{b}"Keyword"@{ub}
          This will highlight any message that contains the text
          enclosed in double quotes.

    @{b}'Keyword'@{ub}
          This does the same as above but is case sensitive.

@{b}Delete Hilite pattern@{ub}
     Select a pattern from the list and press this button to delete it.


@EndNode

@Node "Interface" "AmIRC.guide/Interface"
@Toc "AmIRC Setup"

AmIRC Configuration
*******************

Interface Page
==============

The Interface configuration page allows you to control some specific
aspects of AmIRC that aren't covered in the MUI configuration.

General Page
------------

Windows Limits
--------------

@{b}Scrollback Buffer Size:@{ub}
     Here the size of the Scrollback buffer can be set (in lines).

Misc
----

@{b}Inline URL/Email handling@{ub}
     Here you can determine if AmIRC will sent the URL or Email address
     to your browser or email client by either single or double mouse
     click. Or you can disable it completely.

@{b}Timestamps@{ub}
     With this you can determine if the time stamps that appear in
     front of each entry in the channel list will be either
     @{i}Short@{ui}(hh:mm) or @{i}Long@{ui}(hh:mm:ss), or you can disable them.

@{b}Window list action@{ub}
     You can make the window either @{i}Uniconify/Iconify@{ui}, where the
     windows will just re-open when uniconified, or @{i}Uniconify/Pop@{ui} to
     front, where a window will pop to the front when uniconified.

@{b}Remember buffer position when iconified?@{ub}
     When this item is selected AmIRC will remember the buffer position
     when it is being iconified.  When the interface is brought back up
     it will be at the same position in the buffer.

@{b}Hide page manipulation buttons?@{ub}
     You can hide the buttons with which you can manipulate the pages.

Wheel mouse support
-------------------

@{b}Wheel scroll lines:@{ub}
     Here you can determine how many lines will be scrolled at a time
     when the mouse wheel is used.

Channels Page
-------------

Fonts
-----

@{b}Channel text font@{ub}
     Here you can specify an alternative channel text font that will be
     used in the main channel list. If none is specified the font set
     in the MUI Prefs will be used.

Userlist
--------

@{b}Userlist@{ub}
     You can determine if the user list is visible or not visible, and
     if it is visible, if it is a separate window, or a part of the
     AmIRC window.

@{b}Order@{ub}
     This gadget determines how the userlist will be shown. Either in
     @{i}Alpabetical Order@{ui}, @{i}New at bottom@{ui} or @{i}New at top@{ui}.

@{b}Popup Menu@{ub}
     You can select the Userlist popup menu to be @{i}Disabled@{ui}, @{i}Same as
     Action Buttons@{ui} or @{i}Complex(Hierarchical)@{ui}.

@{b}Buttons?@{ub}
     You can have the Action buttons displayed below the user list.  If
     the user list is configured as a separate window, the buttons will
     also appear in that window.

@{b}Userlist win open?@{ub}
     The userlist window can be opened upon start-up, if it is
     configured as a separate window.

Misc
----

@{b}No Balance Bar?@{ub}
     You can disable the Balance Bar between the user list and the
     channel list.

@{b}Hide Lag-O-Meter?@{ub}
     You can hide the Lag-O-Meter from the main window.

@{b}'Economy' channelmode buttons@{ub}
     In 'Economy' mode the channel mode buttons are merged into a
     single button containing all the relevant switched that are set,
     leaving more space for other interface items.  If you want to set
     a channel mode you can click on the button to pop up the channel
     mode buttons

Dialogs Page
------------

Fonts
-----

@{b}Dialog window font@{ub}
     Here you can specify an alternative dialogue window font that will
     be used in the dialogue windows. If none is specified the font set
     in the MUI Prefs will be used.

Windows Limits
--------------

@{b}Maximum number of query windows:@{ub}
     Here you can set how many QUERY windows there will be open maximum
     at a time.

@{b}No query windows when away?@{ub}
     You can disable QUERY windows from opening when you are set @{"AWAY" Link "AWAY"}.

Misc
----

@{b}Query window on different Pubscreen@{ub}
     Here you can set an alternative public screen on which the @{"QUERY" Link "QUERY"}
     window will be opened. If no pubscreen is specified, the Query
     Window will open on AmIRC's default screen.


@EndNode

@Node "Colors" "AmIRC.guide/Colors"
@Toc "AmIRC Setup"

AmIRC Configuration
*******************

Colors Page
===========

Text Colors
-----------

In this section, you may configure the colours that certain text will
appear in AmIRC. These colours are based on the MUI pen colours that
you have configured in MUI. Just click and hold on the cycle gadget to
see a list of the MUI Pen colours available.

@{b}Normal Text@{ub}
     Text that is a normal message from a user.

@{b}Private Messages@{ub}
     Text that is a private message from another user to you.

@{b}Mode Changes@{ub}
     Text that shows a mode change for the channel.

@{b}Local Info@{ub}
     Text that is generated by local events. E.g. Vapor's MicroDot-2
     notifying you of new mail.

@{b}Background@{ub}
     The background colour of the listview(s).

@{b}Own Text@{ub}
     Any text entered by you.

@{b}Nick Related@{ub}
     Any text that contains a nick action.

@{b}Part Messages@{ub}
     Text when someone leaves a channel.

@{b}Quit Messages@{ub}
     Text when someone quits IRC.

@{b}Invite Messages@{ub}
     Text of an invitation to a channel.

@{b}WhoIs Text@{ub}
     Text produced by the @{"WHOIS" Link "WHOIS"} command.

@{b}Notify Messages@{ub}
     Text of notify messages

@{b}Highlighted Text@{ub}
     Text that is configured in the @{"Hilite" Link "Lists"} list for AmIRC.

@{b}Server Messages@{ub}
     Text that comes from the server.

@{b}CTCP/DCC Messages@{ub}
     Text that informs you of an incoming @{"CTCP" Link "CTCP"} or @{"DCC" Link "DCC"} request.

@{b}Alt. Background@{ub}
     The alternative background colour of the listview(s), indicating
     that the buffer is scrolled back and you're not seeing new
     messages being entered until you scroll down.

@{b}Notices@{ub}
     Notification texts.

@{b}Join Messages@{ub}
     Text when someone enters a channel.

@{b}Kick Messages@{ub}
     Text when someone is kicked from a channel.

@{b}CTCP Actions@{ub}
     Text produced by a @{"CTCP" Link "CTCP"} action.

@{b}Topic related@{ub}
     Text that contains any topic action.

@{b}WallOps Text@{ub}
     Text meant for all IRC Operators.

@{b}Lists Text@{ub}
     Text produced by the @{"LIST" Link "LIST"} command.

Page/Iconify Buttons
--------------------

Here you can specify the colour of the Page (tabs) and Tray Window
buttons, when their respective channel/chat is not visible, indicating
a special event.

@{b}New Message@{ub}
     Colour of the button when new messages are present.

@{b}Highlight@{ub}
     Colour of the button when items have been highlighted.


@EndNode

@Node "Window" "AmIRC.guide/Window"
@Toc "AmIRC Setup"

AmIRC Configuration
*******************

Windows Page
============

Open which windows on startup
-----------------------------

In this section you can determine which windows will be opened when
AmIRC is started. When the gadget behind an item is checked that window
will be opened.

@{b}Window List?@{ub}
     The Window List or @{i}Tray Window@{ui} holds a button for each opened
     window.

@{b}URL grabber?@{ub}
     The URL Grabber window, keeps track of all URL's (or WWW
     addresses) mentioned on any of the joined channels.

@{b}RAW log?@{ub}
     The RAW Log window contains the raw IRC messages.

@{b}DCC send list?@{ub}
     The DCC send window can be used to monitor all outgoing @{"DCC" Link "DCC"}
     traffic.

@{b}Notify list?@{ub}
     The Notify window holds all nicks you want to be notified of when
     they join IRC.

@{b}Info window?@{ub}
     The Info window shows all redirected messages and a graphical
     representation of current lag to the server.

@{b}Privmsg log?@{ub}
     The Privmsg displays all messages sent to you with @{"MSG" Link "MSG"}.

@{b}DCC recv list?@{ub}
     The DCC receive window can be used to monitor all incoming @{"DCC" Link "DCC"}
     traffic.

Other automatic windows
-----------------------

@{b}'Invite' window?@{ub}
     The 'Invite' window is shown when you are @{"invited" Link "INVITE"} to a channel.


@EndNode

@Node "Logging" "AmIRC.guide/Logging"
@Toc "AmIRC Setup"

AmIRC Configuration
*******************

Logging Page
============

Logging
-------

In this section the default log file name and log directory can be set.
You can also specify if you want to log all Channel windows and Dialog
windows.

@{b}Logfile:@{ub}
     This is the file that is used when @{i}'Enable Logging?'@{ui} item is
     enabled in the @{"AmIRC menu" Link "Menus"}.

@{b}Logfile directory:@{ub}
     This is the directory where all individual log files are stored
     when a Channel or Dialog window is logged.

@{b}Log all Channels?@{ub}
     When this item is checked all Channels will be logged.

@{b}Log all Dialog windows?@{ub}
     When this item is checked all Dialog windows will be logged.

@{b}Log all URLs?@{ub}
     When this item is checked all URLs that appear in the URL Grabber
     will be logged.

@{b}Immediate Logging?@{ub}
     When this item is check AmIRC will start logging immediately when
     started.

Filename Templates
------------------

@{b}Channel log filename:@{ub}
     Here the filename for the channel log files is determined.

@{b}Dialog log filename:@{ub}
     Here the filename for the Dialog window log files is determined.

@{b}URL log filename:@{ub}
     Here the filename for the URL log file is determined.

     The gadget at the bottom lists all valid placeholders for the file
     names.


@EndNode

@Node "FKeys" "AmIRC.guide/FKeys"
@Toc "AmIRC Setup"

AmIRC Configuration
*******************

Function Keys Page
==================

Here you may define the Amiga's ten function keys to insert text into
the input string gadget of AmIRC. By using the keys normally, or with
the @{i}shift@{ui} or @{i}ctrl@{ui} modifiers, you may define up to 30 text input macros
that can be used at the press of a key. This is similar to the function
key macros found on many popular terminal emulation programs.

A @{b}/n@{ub} at the end of a function key definition will send a @{b}<CR>@{ub} after the
text. The function key definitions also allow placeholders, similar to
the @{"user buttons" Link "Operation"}.


@EndNode

@Node "Misc" "AmIRC.guide/Misc"
@Toc "AmIRC Setup"

AmIRC Configuration
*******************

Misc Page
=========

CTCP SOUND handling
-------------------

Here you may set the directory where AmIRC looks for files requested by
incoming @{"CTCP Sound" Link "CTCP"} requests.

@{b}Directory:@{ub}
     Here the directory where AmIRC looks for sounds can be entered.

@{b}Volume:@{ub}
     With this slider the playback volume of the sounds can be set from
     0-64.

Sound Player
------------

@{b}Use external player?@{ub}
     When this item is checked AmIRC will use an external player to
     play the sounds.

@{b}Player command line@{ub}
     This is the command that will be executed when AmIRC uses an
     external player.

CTCP Flood Control
------------------

@{b}Request allowed@{ub}
     The number of CTCP requests allowed from a host is a specified
     time period.

@{b}Flood requests tolerated@{ub}
     The number of flood requests allowed before automatically setting
     an @{"IGNORE" Link "IGNORE"} on the host.

@{b}Time periods (seconds)@{ub}
     The period of time in which the allowed amount of @{"CTCP" Link "CTCP"}'s can be
     requested.

@{b}Period extend (seconds)@{ub}
     Time added to flood period per @{"CTCP" Link "CTCP"} request in case of continued
     flooding.


@EndNode

@Node "ARexx" "AmIRC.guide/ARexx"
@Next "AmIRC Support"
@Prev "Configuration"
@Toc "Main"

AmIRC's ARexx Port
******************

Overview
========

AmIRC supports a versatile ARexx Port.


- Custom scripts -

These scripts are executed on certain events.

 @{" RX_Startup " Link "RX_Startup"}        Startup.amirx       Executed on startup.
 @{" RX_Connected " Link "RX_Connected"}      Connected.amirx     Executed on connection.
 @{" RX_Shutdown " Link "RX_Shutdown"}       Shutdown.amirx      Excuted on shutdown.
 @{" RX_Custom_CTCP " Link "RX_Custom_CTCP"}    Custom_CTCP.amirx   Excuted on unknown CTCP commands.
 @{" RX_DCCDone " Link "RX_DCCDone"}        DCCDone.amirx       Excuted when a DCC is complete.
 @{" RX_HandleFlood " Link "RX_HandleFlood"}    HandleFlood.amirx   Excuted when a CTCP flood is identified.

- Command reference -

 @{" RX_SAY " Link "RX_SAY"}               SAY              Treat something just like it was entered in the input string.
 @{" RX_GETMYNICK " Link "RX_GETMYNICK"}         GETMYNICK        Request current nick name.
 @{" RX_ISCONNECTED " Link "RX_ISCONNECTED"}       ISCONNECTED      Check whether connection is established.
 @{" RX_GETSERVERNAME " Link "RX_GETSERVERNAME"}     GETSERVERNAME    Request current server name.
 @{" RX_USERHOST " Link "RX_USERHOST"}          USERHOST         Query Userhost of a nick.
 @{" RX_ECHO " Link "RX_ECHO"}              ECHO             Echos text to the current listview.
 @{" RX_RAW " Link "RX_RAW"}               RAW              Sends raw text to the server.
 @{" RX_GETWINNUM " Link "RX_GETWINNUM"}         GETWINNUM        Returns the window number for a channel.
 @{" RX_CHANNELS " Link "RX_CHANNELS"}          CHANNELS         Returns string showing joined channels.
 @{" RX_GETDCC " Link "RX_GETDCC"}            GETDCC           Returns status of DCC's to stems.
 @{" RX_GETCHANNEL " Link "RX_GETCHANNEL"}        GETCHANNEL       Returns channel joined in active window.
 @{" RX_GETSELECTEDUSER " Link "RX_GETSELECTEDUSER"}   GETSELECTEDUSER  Returns nick of user selected in userlist window.
 @{" RX_GETUSER " Link "RX_GETUSER"}           GETUSER          Returns the nick of user number in userlist window.
 @{" RX_GETUSERS " Link "RX_GETUSERS"}          GETUSERS         Returns a string with all users in the current channel.
 @{" RX_GETUSERSTATE " Link "RX_GETUSERSTATE"}      GETUSERSTATE     Tells whether the user has Op, Voice, or no privledges.
 @{" RX_GETLINE " Link "RX_GETLINE"}           GETLINE          Waits for the next line and parses it into a stem variable.
 @{" RX_GETLINECOUNT " Link "RX_GETLINECOUNT"}      GETLINECOUNT     Tells you how many lines have been entered since you enterd the
channel.
 @{" RX_GETLASTLINE " Link "RX_GETLASTLINE"}       GETLASTLINE      Returns the last line, unparsed.
 @{" RX_GETAWAYSTATE " Link "RX_GETAWAYSTATE"}      GETAWAYSTATE     Checks if you are marked away.
 @{" RX_GETVERSION " Link "RX_GETVERSION"}        GETVERSION       Tells you what version AmIRC you are using.
 @{" RX_GETCTCPSOUNDDIR " Link "RX_GETCTCPSOUNDDIR"}   GETCTCPSOUNDDIR  Returns CTCP sounds directory.
 @{" RX_GETDCCRECEIVEDIR " Link "RX_GETDCCRECEIVEDIR"}  GETDCCRECEIVEDIR Returns DCC receive directory.
 @{" RX_MATCHUSERHOST " Link "RX_MATCHUSERHOST"}     MATCHUSERHOST    Matches a pattern to a hostname.
 @{" RX_PLAYSOUND " Link "RX_PLAYSOUND"}         PLAYSOUND        Plays a sound via AmIRC.
 @{" RX_PARSELINE " Link "RX_PARSELINE"}         PARSELINE        Returns the line given in a stem variable.


@EndNode

@Node "RX_Startup" "AmIRC.guide/RX_Startup"
@Next "RX_Connected"
@Toc "ARexx"



ARGUMENTS:

None

DESCRIPTION:

This script is executed when AmIRC is launched.  It may be used to
initialise scripts.


@EndNode

@Node "RX_Connected" "AmIRC.guide/RX_Connected"
@Next "RX_Shutdown"
@Prev "RX_Startup"
@Toc "ARexx"

Connected.amirx
===============

ARGUMENTS:

None

DESCRIPTION:

This script is executed once a connection has been established to a
server.


@EndNode

@Node "RX_Shutdown" "AmIRC.guide/RX_Shutdown"
@Next "RX_Custom_CTCP"
@Prev "RX_Connected"
@Toc "ARexx"

Shutdown.amirx
==============

ARGUMENTS:

None

DESCRIPTION:

This script is executed on shutdown of an AmIRC client.  It may be used
to flush memory.

Note: It is imperative to change host address in the beginning of the
script       because the AmIRC arexx port will drop shortly after
shutdown.amirx       is executed.  EXAMPLE :

     /* Shutdown.amirx */
     address REXX


@EndNode

@Node "RX_Custom_CTCP" "AmIRC.guide/RX_Custom_CTCP"
@Next "RX_DCCDone"
@Prev "RX_Shutdown"
@Toc "ARexx"

Custom_CTCP.amirx
=================

ARGUMENTS:

command fromnick destination arguments

where "destination" is either the destination channel or   your own
nickname.

DESCRIPTION:

This script will be executed for every CTCP command received that is
not implemented internally into AmIRC.  When this script exists, the
"Unknown CTCP command ..." line will not be displayed, so include code
to emulate it.

EXAMPLE :

This example shows how to implement a simple page command that plays a
sound and deiconifies the client.

     /* Custom_CTCP.amirx */
     options results
     parse arg command fromnick destination arguments
     
     /* Display unknown CTCP commands */
     if command ~= 'PAGE' then do
         'ECHO P=«CTCP» C=5 Unknown "'command'" request from' fromnick'.'
         exit
     end
     /* Ignore if request was sent to a channel */
     if left(1,destination) ~= '#' then do
         /* echo a line,deiconify client and play a sample */
         'ECHO P=«CTCP» C=5' fromnick 'has paged you.'
         'SHOW'
         'PLAYSOUND Page.WAV'
     end


@EndNode

@Node "RX_DCCDone" "AmIRC.guide/RX_DCCDone"
@Next "RX_HandleFlood"
@Prev "RX_Custom_CTCP"
@Toc "ARexx"

DCCDone.amirx
=============

ARGUMENTS:

com successcode nick filename

where :   successcode is 1 for a successful DCC 0 for failed.    com is
SEND for Outgoing DCC's or RECEIVE for Incoming DCC's.

DESCRIPTION:

This script is executed when a DCC is completed/aborted/failed.  It may
be used to perform automated actions on received files.

EXAMPLE:

This script will extract lha/lzx archives to RAM: and play wav's and
snd's.

     /* DCCDone.amirx */
     options results
     parse arg com successcode nick filename
     
     /*Transfer failed/DCC is incoming - abort*/
     if successcode=0 | com='SEND' then exit
     
     /* Obtain 3 - letter extension */
     ext = upper(right(strip(filename,'B',' "'),4))
     
     /*
     ** #?.wav or #?.snd  will be played in AmIRC
     ** #?.lha will be extracted to RAM:
     ** #?.lzx will be extracted to RAM:
     */
     Select
         when ext = '.WAV' | ext = '.SND' then 'PLAYSOUND' filename
         when ext = '.LHA' then address command 'lha x' filename 'RAM:'
         when ext = '.lzx' then address command 'lzx x' filename 'RAM:'
     otherwise
     end


@EndNode

@Node "RX_HandleFlood" "AmIRC.guide/RX_HandleFlood"
@Next "RX_SAY"
@Prev "RX_DCCDone"
@Toc "ARexx"

HandleFlood.amirx
=================

ARGUMENTS:

:nick!user@host type target :text

DESCRIPTION:

If this script exists,it will be called once AmIRC identifies a CTCP
flood.  It is passed the last flood-line as arguments.  If the script
does not exist, the internal AmIRC function will be used.

EXAMPLE :

     This example will effectively emulate the internal AmIRC flood
     protection.  One may improve on it.
     
     /* Handleflood.amirx */
     options results
     parse arg last
     "parseline" last
     
     parse value last.prefix WITH nick'!'user''host
     
     'SAY /IGNORE *!*'host 'CTCP'
     "ECHO P=FloodProt Flood from" nick "defused."


@EndNode

@Node "RX_SAY" "AmIRC.guide/RX_SAY"
@Next "RX_GETMYNICK"
@Prev "RX_HandleFlood"
@Toc "ARexx"

SAY
===

Usage:
     SAY TEXT/F

DESCRIPTION:

Treats @{b}TEXT@{ub} just like it has been entered in the string gadget of the
current window.

EXAMPLES:

     'say /JOIN #Amigager'

RELATED TOPICS: See @{"RX_ECHO" Link "RX_ECHO"}.


@EndNode

@Node "RX_ISCONNECTED" "AmIRC.guide/RX_ISCONNECTED"
@Next "RX_GETSERVERNAME"
@Prev "RX_GETMYNICK"
@Toc "ARexx"

ISCONNECTED
===========

Usage:
     ISCONNECTED

DESCRIPTION:

Checks whether a connection is currently established. Returns RC 0 if
the link is up, RC 5 otherwise.

EXAMPLES:

     "ISCONNECTED";"ECHO" rc

RELATED TOPICS:


@EndNode

@Node "RX_GETMYNICK" "AmIRC.guide/RX_GETMYNICK"
@Next "RX_ISCONNECTED"
@Prev "RX_SAY"
@Toc "ARexx"

GETMYNICK
=========

Usage:
     GETMYNICK

DESCRIPTION:

Returns your current nickname.

EXAMPLES:

     "GETMYNICK";"ECHO" result

RELATED TOPICS: See @{"RX_GETSERVERNAME" Link "RX_GETSERVERNAME"}.


@EndNode

@Node "RX_GETSERVERNAME" "AmIRC.guide/RX_GETSERVERNAME"
@Next "RX_USERHOST"
@Prev "RX_ISCONNECTED"
@Toc "ARexx"

GETSERVERNAME
=============

Usage:
     GETSERVERNAME

DESCRIPTION:

Returns the name of the IRC server you are currently connected to.

EXAMPLES:

     "GETSERVERNAME";"ECHO" result

RELATED TOPICS: See @{"RX_GETMYNICK" Link "RX_GETMYNICK"}.


@EndNode

@Node "RX_USERHOST" "AmIRC.guide/RX_USERHOST"
@Next "RX_ECHO"
@Prev "RX_GETSERVERNAME"
@Toc "ARexx"

USERHOST
========

Usage:
     USERHOST NICK/A

DESCRIPTION:

Returns the userhost specification belonging to @{b}NICK@{ub}.  AMIRC keeps an
internal list of the userhosts of every nick that occurred yet. You can
query this database with this command.  Note however that it is
possible that the userhost isn't in the database yet; this command will
@{i}not@{ui} query the server then, but simply return an error.

EXAMPLES:

     "USERHOST Olli";"ECHO" result

RELATED TOPICS: See @{"RX_GETMYNICK" Link "RX_GETMYNICK"}.


@EndNode

@Node "RX_ECHO" "AmIRC.guide/RX_ECHO"
@Next "RX_RAW"
@Prev "RX_USERHOST"
@Toc "ARexx"

ECHO
====

Usage:
     ECHO P=PREFIX/K,C=COL/K/N,TEXT/F/A

DESCRIPTION:

Sends text to the listview.  With P=Text you can set the prefix which
will be put in the Prefix part of the echo.  With C=Colour you can set
any of the colours set in the AmIRC configuration. The colours you can
use are :
@{b}C=0 : Normal Text@{ub}
@{b}C=1 : Highlighted Text@{ub}
@{b}C=2 : Private Messages@{ub}
@{b}C=3 : Server Messages@{ub}
@{b}C=4 : Mode Changes@{ub}
@{b}C=5 : CTCP/DCC Messages@{ub}
BUGS:

AmigaDOS Readargs() has a small bug.

If you do "ECHO P" or "ECHO P=Prefix P is a letter" or "ECHO C" or
"ECHO C=1 C is a letter"

AmIRC will not display anything.  To cure this enter the template in
full like: "ECHO TEXT=P..."

EXAMPLES:

     "ECHO P=Kewlja C=3 This is echo test"


@EndNode

@Node "RX_RAW" "AmIRC.guide/RX_RAW"
@Next "RX_GETWINNUM"
@Prev "RX_ECHO"
@Toc "ARexx"

RAW
===

Usage:
     RAW TEXT/F

DESCRIPTION:

Sends text to the server in raw format.

EXAMPLES:

     "RAW PRIVMSG phalanx :heya! what's happening?"


@EndNode

@Node "RX_GETWINNUM" "AmIRC.guide/RX_GETWINNUM"
@Next "RX_CHANNELS"
